<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Veto 3rdLd-Writethru a0723 11-20 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Veto, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0723,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Vetoes District Of Columbia Bill Over Abortion Funds</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf with Senate passage of bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD AIR FORCE ONE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Monday vetoed the
annual bill appropriating money for the District of Columbia
because it would allow funds from local taxes to be spent on
abortion.
   It was Bush's second abortion-related veto in two days. With
Congress eager to adjourn before Thanksgiving and no chance for an
override, the House by voice vote immediately passed a new bill
without the objectionable provision and sent it to the Senate,
which followed suit just before midnight.
   On Sunday Bush vetoed the $14.6 billion foreign aid bill because
it contained $15 million for a United Nations population control
agency that operates in China. Bush said aid to the U.N. agency
would make the United States a party to coerced abortions resulting
from China's one-child-per-family policy.
   ``Are there no limits to how far this president will go to show
poor women who's boss in this country?'' complained Rep. Les
AuCoin, D-Ore. ``Now we see the president trying to be the mayor of
the District of Columbia.''
   But the veto was hailed by an anti-abortion organization. ``God
bless President Bush for refusing to sign a death warrant for 3,000
unborn babies,'' Susan A. Smith, spokeswoman for the National Right
to Life Committee, said in a statement.
   It was the second time Bush vetoed the D.C. appropriations bill
over the abortion issue. His earlier veto was in October.
   The president, who was returning to Washington from a campaign
trip on behalf of two pro-choice Republican candidates, sent a
message to the House saying the bill was ``unacceptable.''
   Bush said the bill ``would permit congressionally appropriated
local funds to be used for abortion on demand with no restriction
whatsoever. As a matter of law the use of local funds in the
District of Columbia must be approved by the Congress and the
president.''
   White House Chief of Staff John Sununu spoke with House Speaker
Thomas Foley, D-Wash., earlier Monday, and Foley asked for quick
action on the bill so Congress would have a chance to act again
before leaving for the holidays, according to presidential
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   The bill would have restricted use of Medicaid funds for
abortions only to save the life of the mother. But Bush objected to
what he called ``abortion on demand'' paid for with other funds
derived from local taxes but also appropriated by Congress.
</TEXT>
