<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-Santa     11-20 0808</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Santa,0829</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ja, Virginia, Santa Comes Early To Happy Berlin This Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HUGH A. MULLIGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Corresondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ja, Virginia, es gibt einen Nikolaus _ there
is a Santa Claus.
   Traditionally, the jolly old bagman with the braumeister's belly
doesn't make the German scene until Dec. 6, the feast of St.
Nicholas, but Christmas is pouring through the holes in the Berlin
Wall weeks ahead of schedule.
   Like old Fezziwig in Charles Dickens' ``A Christmas Carol,'' the
whole city, East and West, is ``one vast substantial smile.''
   Instead of growing furious at the 2 million poor relations
thronging the chic downtown streets, and at the clouds of exhaust
rising from the endless influx of snorting two-cylinder East German
cars, the ``Wessis'' welcome the ``Ossis'' with smiles, flowers,
champagne, and a government welcome gift of $54 spending money.
   For the children, arriving wide-eyed with wonder, these weekend
shopping sprees are like being invited into Santa's workshop for
advance consultation on their wish list.
   But it is the old people, who remember Berlin before the war and
especially before the wall and thought they would never see it
again, who now really believe in Santa Claus.
   ``Ein traum wird wirklichkeit'' _ a dream come true _ murmured a
middle-aged matron trying on a pair of $215 Charles Jourdan red
satin evening pumps Saturday in the ground-floor designer boutique
at West Berlin's sprawling KaDeWe department store.
   ``Of course she will never buy them,'' whispered sales clerk
Jacqueline Brenz. ``But for once her life, let her walk up and down
on the carpet and dream she is Princess Diana.''
   A few aisles away, a team of beauticians from Paris demonstrated
a new line of Guerlain cosmetics called Samsara.
   They coaxed a frumpy East Berlin woman onto the model's tall
stool, tweaked and blackened her eyelashes, applied a magenta
lipstick, removed the shadow of a mustache with brush strokes of
peach pancake makeup and fluffed out the steely gray hair that had
been primly pinned up in a bun.
   ``Maurice Chevalier said there is no such thing as an old
woman,'' the fashion coordinator intoned in German into his hand
microphone. ``Only a more mature, more experienced woman.''
   The audience of East Germans blocking the aisle laughed
uproariously at the blushing grossmutter, who liked what she saw in
the mirror.
   It was already 20 minutes past closing time, but Santa's elves
in the third-floor toy department patiently demonstrated a
computerized ``chess tutor'' and the ``hi-tech talking robot'' to
an enthralled knot of East Berlin youngsters.
   ``You can tell Easties by the way they dress,'' toy salesman
Peter Rabinsky said. ``They come bundled up in those bulky winter
jackets with a woolen scarf wrapped around six times and a ski cap
down over the ears, which the parents never remove in the hot
store. They wear those bulky boots and all are carrying those
plastic East Berlin shopping bags.''
   He was interrupted by 11-year-old Dieter Drager, eager to plunk
down $16 for the model kit of ``Lockheed's U2-R Spy Plane.''
   Coming from Potsdam, the Drager family had crossed the border
over the famous spy-swapping Glienicke Bridge, where on another
Saturday 27 years ago American U-2 pilot Francis Gary Powers was
traded for Russian master spy Rudolf Abel.
   Eric's father, a dairy equipment mechanic, had never heard of
that classic Cold War barter, but as if to redress the balance of
power, Hans, his 9-year-old, invested $14.50 in a MiG-31 Foxhound.
   ``They love model planes, autos and boats. Unfortunately they
cannot use our model railroad kits, because like the East German
tram cars their toy trains run on a wider gauge track,'' Rabinsky
said.
   In the sprawling sixth-floor food hall, the visitors from across
the Spree River marveled at ``45 kinds of bologna'' in the
refrigerated showcase.
   They stocked up for the holidays on ``Guatemala Real Kaffee,''
Sir Winston Tea by the kilo, as well as chestnuts for roasting by a
steam radiator in a state apartment block. A sales girl in a
Bavarian costume doling out hot samples of tinned klopse _
dumplings _ found herself operating a sizeable soup kitchen as word
spread.
   Along the broad Kurfuerstendamm shopping boulevard, mobbed like
Cologne at carnival or Leipzig during a Monday demonstration,
street hawkers singled out East German toddlers for the gift of a
balloon twice their size. A benevolent food vendor offered ``DDR
Burgers'' for one East German mark, with a value of maybe five
cents and falling.
   A teen-ager in a green apron at the Burger King cash register
pretended not to notice when a frail old man leaning on a cane paid
for his ``Doppel Whopper'' with a five-mark note drawn on ``Der
Deutschen Demokratischen Republik,'' the official name of East
Germany. She made up the difference from her purse.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
