<FIRST>r i PM-EGermany-Luxury     11-20 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-EGermany-Luxury,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Describes Communist Comrades' Luxury Homes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Communist Party newspaper, exercising the
new openness, described for East Germans how top party officials
came to acquire luxury home furnishings from abroad while their
countrymen had to do without.
   ``Canadian lumber, Italian floor mosaics, West German bathroom
tiles ... in grand one-family houses with immense floor space,''
was how the Berliner Zeitung described the officials'
well-appointed homes.
   Party officials who over four decades of unchallenged one-party
rule took advantage of their high positions to enrich themselves
are widely resented.
   There is a desperate shortage of construction materials in East
Germany, and many people live in cramped apartments with relatives.
   Nonetheless, the newspaper said a state-owned Potsdam firm _ VEB
Spezialbau Potsdam _ has in years past been responsible for
arranging for the import of expensive furnishings for the homes of
high-ranking party officials.
   The firm's normal task is maintenance of buildings housing
Soviet troops in East Germany, the newspaper said in the article
Sunday.
   ``We got simply everything, from wherever,'' it quoted one
former employee as saying.
   Many top party officials live in an exclusive community north of
Berlin called Wandlitz.
   Egon Krenz, the country's new Communist leader, said in an
interview with East German television Sunday night that the
situation was changing.
   Krenz said that he had, since becoming party chief on Oct. 18,
moved into a concrete building in East Berlin's Pankow district.
The home appeared comfortable but modest.
   ``I feel like a Berliner now,'' Krenz said in the interview.
</TEXT>
