<DOCNO> AP891120-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 0047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BlackMigration     11-20 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Black Migration,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Elderly Blacks Moving Both North and South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elderly blacks, many of whom head home to the
South when they retire, later move back north in significant
numbers, say researchers who express surprise at the finding.
   A stream of elderly blacks heading from states like New York to
Florida was expected, but the counter-flow was ``something nobody
had even imagined before,'' said sociologist Charles F. Longino of
the University of Miami.
   ``We don't know if they are going back home to be with their
kids, or what,'' said Longino in a telephone interview.
   Longino, a specialist in the elderly, and Kenneth J. Smith
reported their findings in a paper ``Roots: Black Return Migration
to the South,'' presented this weekend at a gerontological meeting
in Minneapolis.
   Their finding of a large flow of elderly blacks from North to
South duplicates earlier studies for the population in general.
However, since blacks and whites have different rates of
relocation, the researchers did not compare the races.
   Comparing people's residence as reported in the 1980 census with
their homes five years earlier and their place of birth, Longino
and Smith found that major retirement streams flow in the reverse
of historical black labor routes.
   In other words, many southern blacks left home for jobs in the
North in their youth, but returned home to friends, family and
lower costs of living when they retired. Later, however, many
reversed that move.
   The study was based on the movements of about 75,600 elderly
blacks over five years.
   Of those people, the South saw 43,520 move in and 30,720 leave.
The West gained 10,120 and lost 6,000. The Northeast received 9,160
and lost 21,880. And 12,800 arrived in the Midwest, while 17,000
departed.
   ``The older migrants entering the southern region tend to be
younger, more often married, and living independently while those
leaving the South are older, more often widowed and much more
likely to be living dependently at their destination,'' said
Longino and Smith.
   For example, the average age of elderly blacks moving to the
South was 68.5, 45 percent of them were married and 19.5 percent
were disabled. For those moving back north the average age was
72.9, only 21 percent were still married and 29.8 percent were
disabled. Some 72.4 percent of those moving south lived
independently, while only 47 percent going back north maintained
their own household.
   One possibility, Longino suggested, is that older blacks who are
widowed and become dependent may head back north to be with their
children. Another guess, the researchers suggested, is that they
may retire and move south to care for their own elderly parents,
later returning north after those parents die.
   ``To construct a likely scenario from these few population
characteristics is like making an archeological reconstruction from
only a few artifacts,'' they said.
   Overall, the researchers found that the largest numbers of older
persons, which the researchers defined as aged 60 and over, moved
from New York to Florida, North Carolina, South Carolina and
Virginia. In addition, a significant retirement stream was reported
from Illinois to Mississippi.
   California was the leading attractor for black elderly people,
however, a finding that the researchers termed ``contrary to our
research expectations.'' Many of those heading for California came
from Texas and New York.
   Looking at people moving into states, the study found nine
states in which more than half of the older blacks moving in had
been born in that state _ Virginia, West Virginia, North Carolina,
South Carolina, Georgia, Alabama, Mississippi, Arkansas and
Louisiana.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
