<FIRST>r i PM-Hugo-Homeless Bjt   11-20 0726</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo-Homeless, Bjt,0750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Thousand Homeless Still in Shelters Long After Hurricane</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANOVANAS, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For two months, Evelyn Sanchez,
her husband and four children have slept on three mattresses spread
on the tile floor of an elementary school.
   ``We're so tired of it,'' said Ms. Sanchez.
   The family lost their home and possessions when Hurricane Hugo
slammed into Puerto Rico on Sept. 18.
   Taking clothes, a TV set and a tape player, Ms. Sanchez said the
family rode out the storm at Luiz Munoz Marin School, a hurricane
shelter on the outskirts of the coastal town of Canovanas, 35 miles
northeast of San Juan.
   ``But God, we never expected to be here this long,'' said her
common-law husband, Jose Ramos Rodriguez, a garbage collector.
   They are among more than 500 people waiting for federal aid and
temporary housing in Canovanas, the town with the largest number of
homeless hurricane victims in Puerto Rico.
   Throughout the island last week, more than 4,000 homeless people
were being housed in 118 shelters, still waiting for assistance. A
day after the hurricane, the number of homeless reached 12,243.
   Despite the efforts of thousands of emergency workers and local
volunteers, just 10 percent of nearly 160,000 people who applied
for aid with the Federal Emergency Management Agency, or FEMA, have
received assistance. Some 80,000 people have sought help with the
Red Cross.
   Relief workers say the delays are due to the large numbers of
people and homes affected by the devastatiing hurricane.
   ``This is by far the biggest disaster we have ever dealt with,''
said Red Cross spokesman Steve Grumbacher. ``It is the most
expensive and complicated too because the area is so large and
because of the language situation. It's a monster.''
   Puerto Rico is a U.S. commonwealth, but Spanish is the main
language of its 3.3 million inhabitants and only an estimated 58
percent speak English.
   ``It's also been a lousy year for disasters,'' said Grumbacher.
``There was Hugo in the Caribbean and then it hit Carolina. Then
came the San Francisco quake.''
   FEMA spokesman John Schad said that compared with the number of
hurricane victims along the Carolina coast, the number of
applicants for aid in Puerto Rico ``is three times as high.''
   ``We are asking people to please be patient,'' said Schad.
``Obviously with the high numbers of applications, it's going to
take some time.''
   Gov. Rafael Hernandez Colon has accused FEMA inspectors of being
``arbitrary.''
   ``There is a big difference between my estimates and FEMA's,''
the governor said recently, referring to the number of people the
agency determined had lost everything.
   FEMA estimates 8,000 people suffered total losses, while
Hernandez Colon said the figure is about 28,000. About 50,000 homes
were affected by the hurricane.
   Schad said that by Tuesday, the deadline, FEMA expected to have
200,000 or more applications to process. He said 70 to 80 percent
of those applying would be eligible for assistance.
   So far, the agency has issued more than 15,000 checks providing
some $32 million in housing relief, as well as small business
loans, Schad said.
   It's not just assistance which is slow in coming.
   Some 20 to 30 percent of the houses in 17 towns still lack
electricity and running water.
   In stark contrast to San Juan, where only traces of the
hurricane's wrath remain, slabs of wood and tin roofs litter roads
around Canovanas. In the adjacent towns of Loiza Aldea and Rio
Grande, hundreds of fallen palm trees lie on sandy beaches.
   The government had built 883 pre-fabricated units, or modules,
as temporary housing for hurricane victims in 22 towns.
   But that still left many out and they have been waiting in
impersonal shelters.
   ``At first I was hopeful,'' said Jorge Bonano, a 23-year-old
electrician living in a Canovanas shelter with his wife Wanda, who
is five months pregnant. ``They told us the houses would be ready
the 15th of October. Then they said the 31st. Now, I don't know ...
''
   Many of the homeless, impatient for either aid or homes, were
squatting on government land or vacant lots and building their own
makeshift shacks out of whatever material they could find.
   ``It's what a lot of people are doing are doing in
desperation,'' said Evelyn Sanchez. ``It's what we are thinking of
doing.''
</TEXT>
