<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 0107EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Nancy'sReviews     11-20 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nancy's Reviews,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>She Wrote `My Turn' _ Now Critics Take Their Turn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nancy Reagan wrote her memoirs, ``My Turn'' to
get revenge, but what she got was panned.
   Critics, who always get the last word, have been knocking her
book as shallow and mean-spirited, describing it as revealing more
about the author than she might have wanted revealed.
   A few have been friendlier, finding an unexpected side of the
former first lady _ humor.
   In the Chicago Tribune, Dorothy Collin called the book as much
fun as ``a long gossipy lunch.''
   And Florence King, writing in the San Jose (Calif.)
Mercury-News, saluted Mrs. Reagan's deftness in dismissing daughter
Patti's excuse for skipping the 1985 inaugural _ her husband had to
work.
   In a line Ms. King liked a lot, Mrs. Reagan wrote: ``It seemed
to me that if you were taking a couple of days off because your
father-in-law was being sworn in as president of the United States,
most people would understand.''
   But for the most part, the reviewers said Mrs. Reagan has
produced what Barbara Ehrenreich in the New Republic calls a
``whining'' book.
   The Philadelphia Inquirer's reviewer, Susan Page, suggested that
``My Turn'' should have been titled ``Take That.''
   David Lauter of the Los Angeles Times found the book ``a
relentless settling of scores,'' displaying ``cattiness.''
   Concluded Lauter: ``The result is to reinforce virtually every
aspect of the image she would like to shed.''
   ``Nancy Reagan has written a book she shouldn't have,'' agreed
Richard Dyer in the Boston Globe. ``Instead of changing a
hoity-toity image she is unhappy with, she has reinforced it. If
you thought she cared too much about clothes and furniture and
china and decoration and every form of appearance, this book proves
you are right.''
   ``Smugness infects these memoirs,'' said R. W. Apple Jr. in The
New York Times. ``Mrs. Reagan's self-satisfaction and
self-righteousness shine out from page after page.''
   Historian Lewis Gould of the University of Texas, who
specializes in first ladies, says he suspects Mrs. Reagan comes
across as more bitter than she intended. That happens, he says,
when people dictate memoirs into a tape recorder, allowing a
ghostwriter to polish their words.
   By not having to put pen to paper, the author does not have to
think about what he is saying and the result, Gould says, can be
``like a heated letter you read the next morning and throw away.''
   Mrs. Reagan, he said, ``sent out the heated letter.''
   The former first lady, of course, gets the last laugh _ the one
that is laughed en route to the bank. Her book is selling well.
   ``My Turn'' jumped to first-place on most best seller lists. It
took the No. 2 spot on the widely-watched New York Times best
seller list for Nov. 19 and, says her agent, Mort Janklow, it will
reign as No. 1 in the list the Times will print Nov. 26.
   Mrs. Reagan was widely reported to have been paid $2 million in
advance royalties. Random House, her publisher, disputes that
figure but won't disclose the actual amount. Industry scuttlebutt
is that it may have been more.
   Random House publicist Carol Schneider said the first wave of
reviews were ``political.''
   ``People seem to be reviewing Nancy Reagan rather than the
book,'' she said.
   Agent Janklow says the reviews have been negative because people
expect a first lady to write a sweet and innocent memoir, something
Mrs. Reagan's isn't.
   ``She unburdens herself of her pent-up anger and I think that's
what makes it a wonderful book,'' says Janklow.
   Many critics comment on the book's anger. Washington Post
reviewer Sally Quinn said she turned back the corners of pages on
which Mrs. Reagan mentioned being angry, furious, outraged,
irritated or annoyed and counted 42 turned corners in 370 pages.
   One of the targets of Mrs. Reagan's anger was Ms. Quinn herself
for ``a very negative article about me''; another was Ms. Quinn's
husband, Post executive editor Benjamin C. Bradlee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891120-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 0111EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Cheney-Defense     11-20 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cheney-Defense,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney Plans Defense Spending Cuts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney says he is
ordering the military services to plan spending cuts next year
because the rapid pace of Soviet bloc reform reduces the threat of
war to a 45-year low.
   ``It's clear that the likelihood of all-out conflict between the
U.S. and the Soviet Union, between NATO and the Warsaw Pact, is
probably lower now than it's been at just about any time since the
end of World War II,'' Cheney said Sunday on the ABC-TV program,
``This Week With David Brinkley.''
   Cheney said the Soviets appear to be cutting military spending,
and that further U.S. defense reductions are acceptable _ a shift
in his position.
   ``You can't watch the events unfold in Eastern Europe, the
development of governments headed by non-communists, the
possibilities of free elections, of opposition parties, and not
believe that that will have some long-term impact upon the security
situation in Europe,'' Cheney said.
   ``Given the changes that we see today in Eastern Europe, I think
it's possible to contemplate the possibility over the next few
years that we may, indeed, be able to reduce the level of our
deployments in Western Europe,'' Cheney said.
   Two former White House national security advisers also said
Soviet bloc reforms enable America to reduce its troops in Europe.
   ``The pattern of postwar politics as it has developed for the
last 40 years is now at an end,'' Henry Kissinger, the former
national security adviser and secretary of state from the Nixon and
Ford administrations, said on ABC.
   Zbigniew Brzezinski, President Carter's security adviser, urged
that billions of dollars be shifted from defense to help East
European nations move from communism to democracy and a free-market
economy.
   Brzezinski, appearing on the NBC-TV program ``Meet the Press,''
called for creation of a fund for Central Europe modeled on the
Marshall Plan that promoted the economic recovery of Western Europe
after World War II.
   ``We spend about $150 billion on the defense of Europe, about
half of our defense budget,'' Brzezinski said. ``If we can reduce
the level of the confrontation in Central Europe, we will gain
flexibility in dealing with Central Europe economically,
financially, that we haven't had until now.''
   Cheney did not specify how great a reduction he anticipated, but
senior Pentagon officials have said he plans to cut $180 billion
over three years beginning with 1992. Congress is now completing
action on a $286 billion defense budget for the 1990 fiscal year
that began Oct. 1.
   In an interview with The Washington Post published Sunday,
Cheney said the spending cuts for 1991-97 would center on such high
technology hardware as the B-2 stealth bomber. The New York Times
reported that the Air Force has proposed closing 15 bases and
reducing deliveries of F-16 fighters to achieve overall cuts of $34
billion, about $10 billion short of the reduction Cheney has
requested over three years.
   The Soviets have reduced their spending on conventional arms,
Cheney said, but continue to modernize their strategic nuclear
force and have ``a long way to go to clean up their act in the
Third World.''
   He said the Soviet Union was in part to blame for the guerrilla
offensive in El Salvador because Moscow supports Cuba and
Nicaragua, two nations the Bush administration has accused of
aiding the Salvadoran rebels.
   Cheney said he would forward his recommendations on the defense
budget to President Bush in early December, about the time the
president is to hold his first summit with Soviet President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev. The budget package will be sent to Capitol Hill in
January, said Cheney.
   The decision to plan for the cuts was driven in part by the
perception that the Soviet threat was diminishing and in part by
the U.S. budget crunch. Cheney has maintained that Soviet military
spending has risen by 3 percent annually from 1985 to 1988, and
that Pentagon spending has fallen 11 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
