<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru   11-20 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0801,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS to UPDATE with closing Nikkei, dollar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After eight days of consecutive gains, the key
index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange fell Monday, while the dollar
edged up against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues lost 70.16
points, or 0.20 percent, ending at 35,893.58. It had gained 87.40
points for a record closing of 35,963.74 Friday.
   The dollar ended at 144.67 yen, 0.69 yen higher than Friday's
close of 143.98 yen. The currency opened at 144.58 yen and moved
between 144.50 yen and 144.75 yen.
   The index reversed its upward trend after its consecutive gains
for the eight trading days, as market players started to sell
issues for profit-taking, mainly due to a reluctance to raise share
prices further, dealers said.
   Nomura Securities' analyst said the yen's weakness also largely
discouraged investors' buying incentive.
   ``Amid uncertainties over the foreign exchange and interest
rates, many market players stepped off to the sidelines,'' the
analyst said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   In currency dealings, the dollar, which opened higher in Tokyo
following gains in New York Friday, remained strong as market
players demanded the dollar for account settlements, traders said.
   A Bank of Tokyo trader said, ``There will be strong demand for
dollars'' during the next three days because of higher standards of
account settlement by Japanese firms this week than in a usual
week's level.
   Other traders said foreign banks were inclined to buy the U.S.
currency since they are expecting a cut by the U.S. government in
the nation's defense budget.
   The Bank of Tokyo trader added the dollar will remain strong
until exchange markets observe a holiday Thursday.
</TEXT>
