<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 0630EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     11-20 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was up slightly against other major
currencies in quiet European trading today.
   Bullion prices were up sharply in moderate trading.
   European foreign exchange dealers said they expected trading to
stay quiet in the absence of any important U.S. economic indicators
due out this week.
   A national holiday in West Germany on Wednesday coupled with the
Thanksgiving holiday in the United States on Thursday have robbed
the market of enthusiasm, dealers said.
   ``There's no interest,'' said one Frankfurt trader. ``No one
wants to do anything. It's very quiet and will stay quiet all
week.''
   Roger Lever, a senior dealer at Arab Banking Corp. in London,
said U.S. defense cuts confirmed Sunday by U.S. Defense Secretary
Dick Cheney will not have much impact on the dollar, especially
since any favorable effects on the U.S. budget deficit will take
some time to emerge, he said.
   In earlier trading in Japan investors bought dollars on rumors
that the U.S. defense budget was being cut. Dealers said the Bank
of Japan intervened selling dollars to keep the yen from falling
too far.
   Bank of Japan Gov. Satoshi Sumita said it is necessary for
central banks ``to maintain close coordination with other countries
to keep currencies stable'' and ``to take appropriate measures.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.69 yen to a closing 144.67 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at a higher rate of 144.70 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Friday:
   _1.8439 West German marks, up from 1.8410
   _1.6325 Swiss francs, up from 1.6315
   _6.2700 French francs, up from 6.2590
   _2.0832 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0770
   _1,354.00 Italian lire, up from 1,353.50
   _1.1705 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1697
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.5560 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5705 late Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $396.90 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $392.25. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $396.05.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $395.90 compared with $391.50 late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 21 cents to close at a bid
$396.40.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.74 a troy
ounce, up from Friday's $5.61.
</TEXT>
