<FIRST>r a PM-IBM-Equipment     11-20 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IBM-Equipment,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Government Expanding Investigation of IBM Equipment Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators are looking into a
possible second instance of the government's paying for new
International Business Machines Corp. equipment only to receive
used goods, according to a published report.
   The Sun reported today that IBM acknowledged last week it had
inadvertantly sold the government used equipment mislabeled as new
in 1984 and 1985.
   IBM said it voluntarily alerted the government to the error as
soon as it was discovered in February 1987 and has been cooperating
in a General Services Administration investigation. The company
attributed the mix-up to administrative error.
   The Sun said a second case involving used IBM equipment is also
now under review, this one in connection with a $544 million Navy
contract awarded to Electronic Data Systems Corp., a major supplier
of IBM equipment, in August 1987. EDS specializes in designing
sophisticated computer systems.
   The contract under review called for EDS to supply computer
software, hardware and services to the Navy.
   Under the EDS bid, IBM hardware and software accounted for about
$134 million of the total $544 million award.
   According to unnamed sources quoted by the Sun, Navy personnel
contacted the FBI after discovering the IBM equipment were used and
not new as required by the contract.
   The newspaper said the FBI is investigating to determine whether
the mix-up was intentional and whether blame belongs to EDS, IBM or
the Navy.
   For the past nine months, the House Government Operations
Committee has been examining allegations the Navy has improperly
favored IBM over other computer makers. Committee hearings are
expected to conclude later this week.
</TEXT>
