<FIRST>r a PM-PhoneStrike     11-20 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phone Strike,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Telephone Company Strikers Return to Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCIS HOPKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking New England Telephone Co. workers began
returning to their jobs today, 15 weeks after contract talks broke
down in August.
   Members of the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers
voted to ratify a new contract Sunday with the NYNEX Corp., parent
to New England Telephone.
   Peter Cronin, spokesman for the company, said late Sunday, ``We
are very pleased that our employees have ratified the contract.''
   About 18,000 IBEW workers went on strike on Aug. 6. The walkout
caused long delays in directory assistance, repairs and
installation services.
   About 40,000 NYNEX workers in New York also have been on strike,
but talks broke off over the weekend between the phone company and
the CWA, which represents the New York employees.
   NYNEX had resolved the larger, regional issues with the unions
last week, covering wages and benefits. Then late Friday night,
IBEW and company negotiators completed a tentative agreement on
local issues.
   Striking IBEW members voted 7-1 in favor of both the regional
and local packages, said George Nadeau, chairman of the T6 Council
in Maine, the administrative branch of the 10 regional locals where
the results were tallied.
   ``Both have been accepted on a comfortable margin,'' Nadeau said
following the final tally Sunday night.
   The vote in New England was held at union locals across the
region. But the contract did not win favor by IBEW members in
Boston.
   Dennis Banks, a business agent for the Boston IBEW, said a sore
point with the union was NET's use of outside contractors to
perform certain jobs. As part of the local negotiations, union
officials wanted the company to end this practice, ``or at least
put a cap on it,'' Banks said.
</TEXT>
