<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia     11-20 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodian Guerrillas Make Major Attacks to Solidify Gains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NATE THAYER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOUENG TRAKUAN, Cambodia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 5,000 guerrillas today
launched major attacks in the northwest to consolidate gains made
over the past two months, guerrilla and other sources said.
   Beginning early today, hundreds of artillery shells could be
heard falling inside Cambodia. The shelling, which continued into
midday, shook houses in the Thai border town of Aranyaprathet.
   Thai military and guerrilla sources said the shelling came from
government positions in response to the guerrilla attacks.
   The guerrillas' main objectives were the town of Svay Chek and
government-held positions around the village of Nimit, said a
senior official of the Khmer People's National Liberation Front in
Aranyaprathet. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Western and Thai military observers on the border confirmed that
a major attack had begun.
   At the Liberation Front's base of Boueng Trakuan, about two
miles inside Cambodia, guerrillas showed off large quantities of
captured weapons, including four 122mm artillery pieces, mortars,
heavy machine guns, assault rifles and ammunition.
   Soviet-built trucks captured from government forces were seen
carrying weapons to forward guerrilla positions at Svay Chek about
12 miles to the southeast.
   More than 1,000 guerrillas attacked Svay Chek, which was
defended by about 600 government troops, said the guerrilla source
in Aranyaprathet.
   The Liberation Front coordinated the attacks with the
non-Communist guerrilla group loyal to opposition leader Prince
Norodom Sihanouk, the source said. The Sihanoukists attacked
government positions at Kok Mon close to the town of Banteay Chamar
in the far northwest, he said.
   The guerrillas failed to take Svay Chek during their biggest
offensive in 11 years beginning in late September. They did,
however, seize the towns of Banteay Chamar, Thmar Puok and Kandoul
as well as many villages and other military positions.
   Thai military sources, who also spoke on condition of anonymity,
said today's attacks were intended to secure those gains in advance
of an anticipated government counteroffensive.
   Large concentrations of Communist Khmer Rouge fighters also
operate in northwestern Cambodia. However, it was unclear how much
of a role they played in the latest attacks.
   The Khmer Rouge is the most powerful group in a three-party
coalition fighting the government in Phnom Penh.
   The Communist group took over Cambodia in April 1975 and killed
or starved hundreds of thousands of people before it was ousted by
a Vietnamese invasion 11 years ago. The Vietnamese installed the
current Cambodian government.
   Vietnam said it withdrew the last of its combat troops in late
September.
</TEXT>
