<FIRST>r i PM-Namibia-SAfrica     11-20 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Namibia-SAfrica,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>South African Troops Head For Disputed Walvis Bay</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WDH2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa's last 1,500 troops in
this territory are withdrawing as part of its transition to
independence, but many are going to a disputed South African
enclave along the coast.
   The area, Walvis Bay, is more than 400 miles from South Africa's
northern border. It is the only deep-water port along Namibia's
coastline.
   The South African soldiers began departing Friday and are to
complete their withdrawal by this Friday. They are leaving military
bases in the northern towns of Grootfontein and Oshivelo.
   The Grootfontein contingent is headed for the South African city
of Upington, and the Oshivelo mechanized division will be based in
Walvis Bay.
   The South-West Africa People's Organization, which won 57
percent of the vote in the territory's independence elections
earlier this month, says it considers Walvis Bay part of Namibia.
   The elected Constituent Assembly will hold its first meeting
Tuesday and begin work on a constitution paving the way for
independence. South Africa has controlled the territory for 74
years.
   South Africa has army, navy and air force bases in Walvis Bay, a
480-square mile patch of land bordered by Namibia on three sides
and the Atlantic Ocean.
   The South Africans claim Walvis Bay under a 19th century
agreement with Britain that made the port separate from the German
colony of South-West Africa that South Africa seized at the end of
World War I.
   South Africa said it will negotiate with Namibia's independence
government over Namibian use of the port.
   Walvis Bay has a population of 26,000, including 9,000 whites.
</TEXT>
