<FIRST>r i PM-Yugoslavia-Mine     11-20 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia-Mine,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explosion Injures One At Mine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEKSINAC, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A methane gas explosion today
rocked a mine where 92 miners lost their lives in a fire, injuring
one person, the Tanjug news agency reported.
   The fire at the Aleksinacki Rudnici coal mine in eastern
Yugoslavia broke out Friday, trapping the 92 miners in a 700-yard
deep shaft. Officials say there is no chance any survived due to
the buildup of toxic fumes.
   Rescuers were still trying to reach the bodies of the miners
today when the explosion occurred at the mine 125 miles south of
Belgrade, in the republic of Serbia.
   Four people working on the mine's conveyor equipment, where the
fire started Friday, have been arrested, officials reported.
   Friday's accident was Seria's worst mine disaster. A rescue
coordinator said the mine was ``the most inflammable in Yugoslavia
due to high concentrations of methane gas.''
   Five years ago experts recommended the mine be closed down after
a string of fatal accidents culminated in the death of 38 miners in
June 1983. In 1965, 128 people died in a coal mine expolsion in the
central region of Bosnia.
