<FIRST>u i PM-Brazil 1stLd-Writethru a0459 11-20 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brazil, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0459,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rightist and Socialist to Contest Brazilian Presidency</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with further returns. Pick up 9th
graf pvs, `Referring to...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JORGE MEDEROS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Socialist Luis Inacio da Silva's lead
widened today in returns that set him up for an ideologically
heated runoff for the presidency with the conservative front-runner.
   With 99.3 percent of the ballots counted, da Silva, of the
radical left Workers Party, had locked up second place with 16.1
percent of the vote. He had a 400,000-vote lead over the
third-place candidate, Leonel Brizola of the center-left Democratic
Labor Party.
   Fernando Collor de Mello, of the rightist National
Reconstruction Party, won the most votes in Wednesday's elections,
gaining 28 percent. Strongly backed by businessmen and the rural
oligarchs that dominate the countryside, he ha a wide margin from
the beginning.
   Brizola had 15.5 percent of the vote in this country of 150
million people. There are 82 million registered voters.
   Jose Francisco Rezek, president of the Superior Electoral Court,
said the remaining votes would not change the outcome because they
are from da Silva strongholds.
   The rest of the vote in Brazil's first direct presidential
elections since 1960 was split among several other candidates.
   With no one receiving a majority, Collor de Mello and da Silva
will meet in a Dec. 17 runoff. The winner takes office in March for
a five-year term.
   Brizola called a news conference Sunday to announce he was not
ready to concede defeat. He said he might ask the Electoral Court
to recheck vote tallies in some regions.
   Referring to possible support for da Silva's candidacy, he said,
``The Workers Party will have to facilitate any accord with the
Democratic Labor Party. They'll have to consider some of our policy
proposals.''
   He did not elaborate.
   Da Silva, a former union leader and now a congressman, ran well
in urban industrial regions. He also surprised many observers by
picking up strong support among poor rural peasants in the north
and northeast, who traditionally vote under the guidance of
conservative landowners.
   Da Silva didn't talk to reporters Sunday, but party leaders held
a news conference in Sao Paulo.
   Party president Luis Gushiken, a federal representative, said
the runoff would be ``polarized between right and left.''
   ``Collor de Mello represents the right-wing elite and is closely
linked to bankers, large landholders and big businessman. Da Silva
represents the people,'' he said.
   The two candidates have sharp differences over key policy
questions.
   Da Silva, known by his nickname of ``Lula,'' has called for an
immediate moratorium of interst payments on the country's $110
billion foreign debt, the Third World's largest. He also proposes a
large-scale agrarian reform program and a huge transfer of wealth
from rich to poor.
   Collor de Mello has been vague on policy, with a platform based
largely on combating Brazil's corrupt state bureaucracy.
   On Sunday, Collor de Mello told reporters da Silva's policy
proposals were so extreme it would ``be impossible for the Workers
Party to broaden their base of support.''
   The runoff will choose a successor to President Jose Sarney, who
by law could not run for re-election. Sarney is a civilian, but he
gained office in 1985 through an electoral college vote coordinated
by the military.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
