<FIRST>r i PM-DengRetirement     11-20 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deng Retirement,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deng Explains His Retirement to Chinese Leaders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former leader Deng Xiaoping said he retired
because he might say crazy things as he ages, a pro-Beijing
newspaper reported today.
   In speech to senior officials, Deng said his retirement was
designed to end the practice of lifetime tenure among top officials.
   ``My last function is to take the lead to abolish lifetime
employment,'' the Chinese-language Wen Wei Po paraphrased Deng as
saying.
   ``When a man grows old, he tends to become stubborn and lose
energy, this cannot be changed by subjective will. I am old now, my
brain still works but I may say crazy things in the future.''
   The speech was made Sept. 4, two months before Deng, 85,
officially resigned from his last Communist Party post, chairman of
the Central Military Commission. He was replaced by his handpicked
heir, party chief Jiang Zemin.
   Deng, the party patriarch, is still believed to be the key force
in Chinese politics because of his prestige and connections.
   Deng also was quoted as saying many foreigners have urged him to
write his memoirs but he does not think it is necessary.
</TEXT>
