<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 0916EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Egypt-PLO     11-20 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Egypt-PLO,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Urges PLO Not to Reject Baker Peace Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAURICE GUINDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hosni Mubarak today for the first
time publicly advised the Palestine Liberation Organization to
accept a U.S. plan for an Israeli-Palestinian dialogue.
   Mubarak told reporters he had not yet received the PLO's reply
to the plan, set forth last month by Secretary of State James A.
Baker III.
   ``President Mubarak expressed his hope that the reply will not
be negative,'' the Middle East News Agency said, without giving the
president's exact words.
   ``We do not put pressure on anyone, but we must help to push the
process forward,'' Mubarak was quoted as saying.
   The comments marked a change in Egypt's stance. Previously,
Mubarak had said Egypt consults regularly with the PLO on peace
moves and ``adopts'' whatever decisions the group makes.
   Baker proposed the dialogue between Israel and a Palestinian
delegation to prepare the ground for Israeli-proposed elections in
the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. The plan elaborates on
Israel's own election plan.
   The elections would choose Palestinian delegates for talks with
Israel on interim autonomy in the two territories. Negotiations on
a final settlement would be held later.
   Israel has told the United States it would accept the Baker
proposal if the Americans provided some assurances _ mainly, that
the PLO would be excluded from negotiations.
   The PLO recently requested clarifications of the Baker plan and
got a reply through Egypt. PLO leaders were reported meeting in the
Tunisian capital last week to formulate a final answer to the
proposal.
   Mubarak denied reports today that the PLO had already sent its
reply to Cairo for relay to Washington.
   But a PLO emissary arrived this afternoon from the Tunisian
capital, and the Middle East News Agency said his mission was to
convey the Palestinian position.
   It quoted Palestinian sources in Tunis as saying the PLO is
holding to its insistence that it alone choose delegates to the
dialogue, and that the dialogue's agenda be open and unconditional.
Both demands run counter to the Israeli position.
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, who announced the
election proposal last May, has insisted there is no possibility of
Israel's relinquishing the West Bank and Gaza in any settlement. He
considers the territories part of the land of Israel.
   Mubarak noted today that the United States opposes Israel's
retaining the territories it has occupied since the 1967 Middle
East war.
   ``Shamir can say what he wants,'' Mubarak said. ``The United
States has said and is saying (it supports trading)
land-for-peace.''
</TEXT>
