<DOCNO> AP891120-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 0920EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Moslems     11-20 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Moslems,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Politicians: Mrs. Aquino Loser, Rebels Winner in Autonomy Vote</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MLA1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Partial returns showed most
southern voters rejecting a regional autonomy plan, and some
politicians said today the results would boost Moslem rebels
demanding an independent Islamic state.
   President Corazon Aquino proposed the plan to satisfy demands
for self-rule by 4 million Filipino Moslems and to end their nearly
20-year secessionist rebellion. However, she never openly
campaigned for the autonomy proposal.
   Moslem rebels and many Christian leaders opposed the plan,
saying it was inadequate. Critics feared an autonomous government
would not be economically viable if it were limited to impoverished
and geographically separated regions.
   Unofficial, partial returns from Sunday's referendum showed
voters in only three of 13 participating provinces and nine cities
wanted to join the autonomous government.
   The Supreme Court has ruled that any province or city where a
majority of the voters approve the plan will join the regional
government.
   ``The people of the proposed autonomous region ... have
spoken,'' Mrs. Aquino told reporters in Manila. ``It is now the
duty of government to carry out what the peole have decided.''
   Complete returns were not expected before Friday. But election
commissioner Haydee Yorac said ``yes'' votes were leading in only
the largely Moslem provinces of Tawi-Tawi, Sulu and Lanao del Sur.
   In predominately Christian areas, voters were rejecting the plan
by margins of up to 30-to-1, according to the returns. In eight of
the nine cities, about 80 percent of the voters rejected autonomy.
   Moslems form the majority in only five of the 13 provinces.
   Some politicians said the rejection by a majority of the voters
would strengthen the position of Moslem rebel Moro National
Liberation Front.
   Zamboanga Mayor Vitalyano Agan, who supported autonomy, said the
outcome was a personal victory for Nur Misuari, exiled chieftain of
the 24,000-member rebel group.
   ``In my assessment, this rejection is a promotion of Misuari as
the people's leader, indirectly, and a rejection of Mrs. Aquino,''
he said. ``We expect more problems in the future because the moral
side of the (Front) will be strengthened.''
   Misuari, who lives in Saudi Arabia, vowed to escalate the nearly
20-year Moslem insurgency regardless of the outcome of the vote.
   Southern Christian politicians and some Roman Catholic Church
leaders also rejected the proposal.
   Despite the Front's opposition, there were no reports of serious
violence. Moslem insurgents raided 10 villages in Maguindanao
province, but no deaths were reported.
   Mrs. Aquino forged a cease-fire with the Moslem rebels in 1986.
Peace talks collapsed in May 1987, but the cease-fire generally has
held. At least 50,000 people have been killed in the insurgency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
