<HEAD>Eastern European Events at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at major developments in Eastern Europe today:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia _ Students begin a sit-in strike at
Prague universities to protest police attacks on demonstrators. A
Communist leader for the first time condemns the bloody crackdown.
Hundreds protest again to demand more freedom from hard-line
Communist rulers, following weekend protests denouncing police
brutality on Friday.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ROMANIA _ The Communist Party opens a party congress, and
President Nicolae Ceausescu denounces the democratic reforms
sweeping most of the rest of the East bloc. Many Western
ambassadors boycot the gathering to protest human rights violations
under Ceausescu.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EAST GERMANY _ A Communist Party daily reports that some
extremists have urged countrymen to sabotage the nation's
electrical system as a form of protest. A public opinion survey by
a West German magazine finds that if free elections were held now,
the Communists would be in third place with just 14 percent of the
vote. About 100,000 people in eight different cities turn out for
pro-democracy protests on Sunday.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SOFIA, Bulgaria _ About 2,000 people take part in another
pro-democracy protest Sunday, a day after the largest rally staged
by dissidents in the country's Communist history, and sign
petitions criticizing the Communist leadership.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ELSEWHERE _ A Japanese newspaper reports that Japan will provide
about $180 million in aid to Poland and Hungary. The money includes
$100 million in a low-interest loan to Poland.
</TEXT>
