<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 1017EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SuspectSlain     11-20 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Suspect Slain,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reputed Mobster Suspected in Death of DEA Agent's Slayer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prime suspect in the slaying of Costabile
``Gus'' Farace, the alleged killer of a federal drug agent, is a
reputed mobster whom the agent had been investigating, published
reports said.
   Police sources said the reputed mobster, Gerald Chilli, 55, had
been overheard to say he would like to kill Farace, New York
Newsday and the Daily News said in today's editions.
   ``Chilli had been mouthing off that if he got ahold of Farace he
would kill him himself,'' the News quoted a police source as saying.
   The FBI has said Farace's slaying probably was ordered by
high-ranked mobsters angry about the scrutiny that the agent's
murder brought them.
   Farace, 29, was shot Friday night as he sat in the front
passenger seat of a car in Brooklyn. He had been the object of a
nationwide manhunt led by about 100 federal agents investigating
the death Feb. 28 of Drug Enforcement Administration agent Everett
Hatcher.
   At the time of his death, Hatcher was trying to infiltrate a
cocaine ring run by the mob and had made cocaine buys from Farace
in an effort to develop a cocaine conspiracy case against Chilli,
Newsday said.
   Chilli and Farace had served prison terms at the same time at
Staten Island's Arthur Kill Correctional Facility, and Chilli
helped foster Farace's mob career, the newspaper said.
   Authorities were hoping a friend of Farace's who was with him
when he was slain, Joseph Sclafani, would provide information to
police. Sclafani was also shot by Farace's killer, but survived and
was in critical condition Sunday at Coney Island Hospital.
   Farace may have been lured to the shooting site thinking he
would be handed letters from his family, according to the News.
Sources said Chilli was the most likely person to have lured him,
Newsday said.
   On Farace's body, authorities found letters from his wife and
mother and photos of his infant son, whom he never had seen, the
New York Post said in today's editions.
   The letters urged him to keep running from authorities.
</TEXT>
