<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-ElSalvador     11-20 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-El Salvador,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says Aid Cutoff to El Salvador Would Be Unacceptable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, declaring he cannot abandon
``a fragile democracy,'' said today that any congressional aid
cutoff to El Salvador would be an unacceptable response to the
murders of six Roman Catholic priests.
   Bush, speaking to reporters at Andrews Air Force Base, Md., as
he left for Chicago, also said he had spoken with Salvadoran
President Alfredo Cristiani over the weekend and ``offered him
technical help in investigating and bringing to justice the people
who did the killing.''
   Bush's comments came as Congress was considering a $14.6 billion
foreign aid bill that includes money for El Salvador. The U.S.
government pumps about $1.5 million a day in economic and military
aid into the small Central American nation, which has been fighting
a leftist insurgency since 1979.
   House Democratic leaders overrode the objections of some
Republicans and cleared the way Sunday night for Rep. George
Miller, D-Calif., to offer an amendment restricting aid to
Cristiani's 5-month-old government.
   The move is in reaction to the killing last week of six Jesuit
priests, which many take as a sign that El Salvador's right-wing
``death squads'' have renewed their activities. Conservatives,
however, want to increase aid to El Salvador to help the government
combat a new offensive by leftist rebels.
   ``We strongly condemn the killing ... and it must stop,'' Bush
said.
   ``This concept of the Congress, of some members, ... on cutting
off aid to El Salvador is absolutely unacceptable to me as
president,'' he said.
   Bush said Cristiani assured him the government was not involved
in the murders.
   ``I believe it,'' the president said. ``And if some renegade
forces were involved, they should be brought to justice. But
absolutely Cristiani would not lie to me on a matter of this
nature.''
   In the past, Congress has restricted aid to El Salvador because
of human rights abuses. Cristiani's ARENA political party has been
linked to death squad acivity in the early 1980s.
   ``This is not the time to undermine a fragile democracy that is
under attack where we've seen the most brutal use of a civilian
population to further a political end on the part of the FMLN,''
Bush said, referring to the leftist insurgency by its Spanish
initials. ``It's totally unacceptable and the day of these Marxist
attacks should end right now.''
</TEXT>
