<FIRST>u a PM-BobbySeale     11-20 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bobby Seale,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bobby Seale Pleads Guilty to Attempting Bad Checks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KRISTI UMBREIT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Black Panther leader Bobby Seale pleaded
guilty to reduced charges today over a bad-check case involving
more than $7,500 in ribs he bought for a cook-off last year.
   Seale, 52, of Philadelphia, pleaded guilty to four misdemeanor
counts of attempting to pass bad checks. Each count carries a
possible penalty of six months.
   Judge William Aurelius set sentencing for Dec. 19.
   Seale's attorney, Terry Gilbert, said he has paid back all the
money for the ribs he bought at a local store and from a stay at a
local hotel, expenses he incurred for his participation in
Cleveland's National Rib Cook-Off from May 23-30, 1988.
   ``I need to get this (case) out of my hair,'' Seale said outside
the courtroom before making his plea.
   In February, he was indicted on charges of passing back checks
totaling $7,767.13 to buy ribs from Seaway Food Service in
Cleveland. The ribs were for his sales booth at the cook-off.
   In May, Seale was indicted again on three counts of passing bad
checks and one count of theft in connection with checks for $3,000
in lodging and other expenses incurred during the visit.
   All the original counts were fourth-degree felonies and together
carried a possible sentence of five years.
   With today's plea, the theft charge was dropped and the charges
of passing bad checks were reduced to misdemeanor charges of
attempting to pass bad checks.
   Seale said cook-off promoters had asked him to lend his name to
the event, assuming his presence would boost sales. Instead, he
said, sales were poor and expenses were high.
   Since leaving the radical Black Panthers group, Seale has
pursued various book projects, including writing a cookbook on how
to fix ribs. He also works as a community liaison for
African-American studies at Temple University.
</TEXT>
