<FIRST>u a PM-Storm-School 2ndLd-Writethru a0513 11-20 0841</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Storm-School, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0513,0861</SECOND>
<HEAD>Counselors Work to Address Grief in Stricken Community</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with quote, detail from funerals,
CORRECT that critically injured children at two hospitals, sted one in
Newburgh; and to recast. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `Sandy Griffin...'. ^LaserPhoto
MDT2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWBURGH, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Coldenham Elementary School pupils
went to school today for a lesson in dealing with grief and dealing
with terror at the site where seven of their classmates were killed
during a tornado.
   No classes were held, but officials staffed the school with
counselors and encouraged parents and children to come in and talk,
or peer through a doorway into the cafeteria where a wall of
concrete and glass shattered during lunchtime last Thursday.
   ``We want people to see that we're trying to get back into
normal,'' said Horst Graefe, director of pupil personnel for the
Valley Central School District. ``We don't want it to be a fearful
thing. The response has been extremely positive. People have come
in, taken a look, gotten their questions answered and have had a
chance to say hello to their friends again.''
   About two dozen mental health workers were at the school to
speak to parents and children. Outside, dozens of flower
arrangements stood in a cold rain against the boarded-up cafeteria
wall. Classes were to resume Tuesday.
   On Sunday, Gov. Mario Cuomo told an estimated 3,000 people at a
memorial service that ``so great a grief cannot be borne without
being shared.''
   ``Today even amid our crushing, frightening pain we remember the
blessing of these children, who were gems to everyone their lives
touched,'' the governor said Sunday night at Valley Central High
School.
   Two funerals were held Saturday, four more this morning, and a
seventh was scheduled for this afternoon. Two children remained in
critical condition at hospitals in in Newburgh and Albany. Sixteen
others either have been treated or released or were listed in
conditions ranging from good to satisfactory at five hospitals.
   Charles Scotto Jr., 7, was buried today along with a stuffed
Garfield doll, a New York Jets pin, baseball cards and a toy
dinosaur.
   ``Try to keep a picture of our Lord Jesus embracing our little
children,'' the Rev. Dominic Leo told mourners as Charles was
buried at a New Windsor cemetery. ``Let that scene be a comfort to
you.''
   At a private service for Joanna Lichtler, also 7, an honor guard
attended from the Coldenham Fire Department, whose members were
among the first on the scene following Thursday's disaster.
   At Sunday night's service, townspeople sang hymns, heard prayers
and tried to make sense of the disaster.
   Sandy Griffin, who brought her three children to the memorial
service, said it was important to be there even if she could only
hear the words over a loudspeaker.
   ``It means a lot to know that everyone cares,'' Griffin said.
``Everyone in this community is sticking together. You have to come
out here because it could have been your kids. If it were my kids I
would want my friends and family around me.''
   Vera DiBitetto stroked the blond hair of her 5-year-old son,
Michael. ``Maybe it will make us all a little more thankful for
what we have right now,'' she said.
   Hundreds of people _ families of the dead, injured and those
lucky enough to survive _ have turned to psychologists and social
workers in the wake of the tornado.
   About 50 to 60 mental health workers were available for families
at the district's schools all weekend.
   Dozens made private pilgrimages to the school over the weekend,
placing flowers in the shadow in the wall, now rebuilt in wood.
``Pray for the children,'' was spray-painted on the wall.
   Hundreds of residents have come to view the scene of the
tragedy, said Nathalie Weeks, Orange County mental health
commissioner.
   `They've been fantastic,'' she said of Newburgh residents. ``I
think families have been so brave and brilliant about coming in and
taking advantage of the counseling.''
   School social worker Larraine Wernow said she asked an
8-year-old survivor to draw a picture to express his grief. The boy
drew a school with a roof, floor and walls.
   But, she said, he was afraid the walls would come tumbling down.
   ``I couldn't give him a full assurance, but I told him it was
very unlikely it would happen again,'' Wernow said. ``I don't like
to lie to children. You can't lie to children.''
   Not just children and their parents are in need of help. Gus
Quist, a Newburgh volunteer firefighter who helped pull children
from the wreckage, said he's still shaken. ``It helps to talk about
it,'' he said.
   Wernow said she spoke with a man who heard about the tornado and
rushed to the school. He couldn't find his child, only learning
after several agonizing minutes that his wife had taken the
youngster home.
   ``He must have lost many years off his life in just those few
short minutes,'' Wernow said.
</TEXT>
