<FIRST>u i AM-Romania-Ceausescu     11-20 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Romania-Ceausescu,0808</SECOND>
<HEAD>Romanian Leader Holds Firm to Hard-Line Course</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Nicolae Ceausescu is pronounced Nih-kohl-EYE Chow-SHESS-koo.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Romania, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicolae Ceausescu, president and
Communist Party leader of Romania, has created a cult of
personality greater than any in Eastern Europe since Soviet
dictator Josef Stalin.
   And despite the democratic changes sweeping the East European
countries around Romania, Ceausescu has firmly rejected similar
reforms.
   During his 24 years as Communist Party leader, he has exercised
absolute power that enabled him to carry out a foreign policy
independent of the Soviet Union and to keep Romanians under
iron-fisted domestic control.
   The old-style Marxist leader invested billions of dollars in a
crash industrialization program that led to widespread food and
energy shortages, and despair for Romania's 23 million people.
   The longer the food lines and the more vocal the people's
complaints, the more harshly the regime cracked down on critics.
   About 30,000 coal miners went on strike in the Jiu Valley in
1977 and 10,000 workers demonstrated in the city of Brasov in 1987
demanding freedom, better living conditions and Ceausescu's ouster.
Police arrested hundreds of demonstrators and their leaders
disappeared in mysterious circumstances.
   At a mass meeting in Bucharest in 1989, Ceausescu said, ``The
triumph of the revolution requires unity, severe discipline and a
spirit of sacrifice. A firm organization is needed as well as a
tested political leader who knows how to unite and lead the
masses.''
   Ceausescu's ``firm organization'' was the Romanian Communist
Party which he turned into a personal instrument after taking it
over in 1965.
   He gradually pushed aside all leaders who opposed his policies
and installed loyalists on the ruling 23-member Politburo,
including his wife, Elena, a chemist.
   The personality cult he encouraged, particularly after he was
sworn in as Romania's first president, took on the trappings of
worship and pervaded nearly all aspects of public life. His
pictures lined the streets in Bucharest and other Romanian cities
and bookstores were full of works attributed to him.
   When he was elected president in March 1974, an official picture
showed him holding a silver scepter as the symbol of authority.
   During the Ceausescu era, Romania, once known as the breadbasket
of the Balkans, became one of the poorest countries in Europe.
   Billions of dollars were spent on industrial and public works
projects, and food was rationed as the government exported all it
could to pay off its foreign debts. The debt was eventually paid
off in the spring of 1989 but the shortages continued.
   A massive secret police kept strict control on religious and
political expression, and dissent was quickly crushed.
   In the new climate of reform encouraged by the Soviet Union,
Romania has became increasingly isolated in both East and West.
   In a speeches at party meetings in 1989 he said strivings for
reform in some Warsaw Pact countries represent an abandonment of
communism.
   The United States and other Western powers originally encouraged
Ceausescu's relatively independent foreign policy stand within the
Soviet-led Warsaw Pact. Two U.S. presidents visited Bucharest,
Richard M. Nixon in 1969 and Gerald R. Ford in 1975.
   Ceausescu, who took power as Communist Party leader on March 22,
1965, continued diplomatic relations with Israel even after other
Soviet bloc countries broke them in the 1967 Middle East War.
   In keeping with his maverick image, he denounced the Soviet-led
invasion of Czechoslovakia in 1968 and afterward refused to allow
any foreign troops in Romania.
   Romania was the only East bloc country to send athletes to the
1984 Olympics in Los Angeles, breaking the Soviet-led boycott.
   Ceausescu placed members of his family in key posts. His wife
was a Politburo member and first vice premier, and by the mid-1980s
she had become the virtual second-in-command of national life and
shared the limelight with her husband.
   Western analysts and knowledegeable Romanians estimate 40
members of his family held top jobs in the party and state
hierarchy.
   Born Jan. 26, 1918, in Scornicesti, Ceausescu was the third son
of a large peasant family. An elementary school dropout, he was
apprenticed as a shoemaker, took a job in a factory and joined the
illegal Communist Party youth organization at age 15. He became a
party member three years later, in 1936.
   Before and during World War II, his communist activities landed
him in jail several times. He became a protege of communist leader
Gheorghe Gheorghiu-Dej, rose quickly in the party, and succeeded
Gheorghiu-Dej after his death.
   He continued Gheorghiu-Dej's policy of one-man, traditional
Stalinist rule.
   ``I don't give orders,'' he once told U.S. Secretary of State
William Rogers. ``I make suggestions. But they had better be
carried out.''
</TEXT>
