<FIRST>r a AM-DeerSeason     11-20 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deer Season,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deer Season Opens; State Shuts Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Schools are closed. Factories have shut
down. Church pews are empty. No, it's not another economic downturn
or natural disaster. It's deer hunting season in West Virginia.
   For the next two weeks, about 320,000 hunters dressed in
fluorescent orange and wielding rifles will be roaming the woods in
search of bucks, and there's not much the rest of the state can do
but wait until they come back.
   ``The whole week is a disaster,'' said Dave Wooddell, president
of Delwood Equipment Co. in Charleston, which sells machinery to
coal and chemical companies. ``As far as any type of business
transaction being done, it's practically nil. Even Christmas is
better.''
   ``It's been happening for 30 years,'' said Bruce Davis, vice
president of Kanawha Manufacturing Co. in Charleston, which makes
steel parts for power plants and heavy industry. Only 10 percent of
the company's work force is expected to show up for work Friday and
for weekend shifts.
   ``They either take a vacation or go AWOL,'' Davis said. ``It's
something we have to live with and work around.''
   It's almost pointless to open schools in most West Virginia
counties during deer hunting season, education officials say.
   ``These boys are all country boys who like to hunt,'' said Paul
Winters, a school principal in Lincoln County, which has given
students and teachers a weeklong vacation this week. ``We've been
in school three months now, and absentee rates are always high
during Thanksgiving week because of deer season, anyway, so it's
time for a break.''
   Schools in 27 of West Virginia's 55 counties close for a full
week, said Carolyn Spangler, a spokeswoman for the state Division
of Education. One county closes schools for four days, 13 counties
close for three days and 14 counties close for two days, Spangler
said.
   Attendance is down at church services, too.
   ``Most of our men are gone,'' said Janet Jett, church secretary
at Mount Pleasant Baptist Church in Elkview. ``It was about half of
what it normally would be last night.''
   If the weather stays clear and dry, hunters will bag about
70,000 bucks before Dec. 1, about 55 percent of the total annual
harvest, say biologists for the state Division of Natural Resources.
   Rifle deer hunting season began Monday. Bow hunting season,
which began Oct. 14, continues through the end of the year. Doe
hunting season runs from Dec. 7 to Dec. 9, and a six-day
muzzle-loading season starts Dec. 18.
</TEXT>
