<FIRST>r i AM-Ethiopia-Talks     11-20 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethiopia-Talks,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talks Open Between Ethiopian Gov't, Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethiopian rebels and government officials
met Monday for a second round of peace talks and accused each other
of impeding progress in ending Africa's oldest civil war.
   Former President Jimmy Carter, serving as a neutral observer at
the talks, said at an opening ceremony that both sides were
``sincere and dedicated'' in their efforts to achieve peace.
   But the delegations, in statements delivered after Carter's
comments, made it clear they were not satisfied with each other's
behavior outside the talks.
   The Ethiopian government delegation accused the rebels of
intensifying ``anti-peace propaganda,'' and the rebel Eritrean
People's Liberation Front said the government was conducting a
campaign of ``fallacious arguments, disinformation and at times
outright blackmail ... to impede the progress underway.''
   The preliminary talks, which began in September in Atlanta, are
aimed at laying the groundwork for substantive negotiations to end
the 28-year-old secessionist war in Eritrea, Ethiopia's
northernmost province.
   Three of 13 questions remain to be resolved during the
preliminary talks: the designation of a chairman and co-chairman
for further discussions, the naming of a seven-member observer team
and the role it is to play, and the selection and duties of a
secretariat.
   Carrie Harmon, Carter's spokeswoman, said Carter and the
seven-member delegations met for about four hours after the opening
ceremony.
   ``The talks went very well,'' said Ms. Harmon. ``They got right
down to work.''
   The closed-door talks are taking place at a house in the Nairobi
area. Carter's wife, Rosalynn, is participating in the negotiations
as she did in Atlanta.
   Ms. Harmon would not comment on whether the delegations made any
progress in resolving the outstanding issues, or whether the
combative tone of the opening statements were reflected during the
talks.
   During the opening ceremony, Ashagre Yigletu, head of the
Ethiopian government delegation, said it was his government's
``fervent desire'' to see the Nairobi talks successfully concluded
and for the main substantive talks to be started as soon as
possible.
   But he said a recent major offensive by Ethiopia's second most
powerful rebel group, which he described as a ``grave and
orchestrated challenge,'' was an ``obstacle to the success of the
current peace talks.''
   The rebel Tigre People's Liberation Front, which operates from
Eritrea's southern neighbor, has pushed steadily southward since
August and is seen as a growing threat to the government in Addis
Ababa.
   Ethiopian President Mengistu Haile Mariam has accused the
Tigrean rebels of trying to further the cause of Eritrean
separatism.
   The rebels accused Ethiopia's government of conducting a
``futile war effort'' in Eritrea ``to escalate its campaign of
dislocation and dispersion, to weaken the Eritrean struggle and
create a de facto divided Eritrea.''
   The statement also spoke of the severe drought in Eritrea that
could threaten nearly 2 million people with starvation, and urged
the international community to provide the resources needed to
stave off widespread famine.
   The Marxist rebels, who hold much of Eritrea, have remained
largely behind lines gained during a major offensive last year.
   The opening ceremony was attended by about 200 diplomats,
Cabinet ministers and journalists. Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
encouraged both sides to continue working together to settle the
fighting, which has killed an estimated 1 million people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
