<FIRST>u a PM-Bush 5thLd-Writethru a0569 11-20 1040</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0569,990</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Campaigns for Two Congresswomen</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs 7th graf, He then, to correct that four sted three
protesters taken out; inserts new 9th graf, A Chicago, with charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, with an early eye on the 1990
elections, went campaigning today in Illinois and Rhode Island for
two Republican congresswomen who disagree with him on abortion.
   The trip came one day after Bush cast his third abortion-related
veto this fall, knocking back a $14.6 billion foreign operations
bill because it included $15 million in aid for a United Nations
population control agency that Bush blames for supporting forced
abortions in China.
   The president made no mention of abortion in remarks at a
fund-raising lunch here for Rep. Lynn Martin, who is challenging
incumbent Democratic Sen. Paul Simon in next year's elections.
   Instead, he made a pitch for cutting the capital gains tax and
passing his anti-crime and clean air initiatives _ all of which
have been held up in the Democratic-controlled Congress.
   As Bush spoke at the $250-a-person Republican fundraiser, he was
heckled by members of the audience who shouted criticism of U.S.
policy in El Salvador.
   When a woman accused the administration of killing priests, Bush
replied: ``We are not. You be quiet.''
   He then sought to explain why the U.S. was supporting El
Salvador. With that, a man jumped up and shouted, ``Stop the
repression in El Salvador.'' The two demonstrators and two other
women were led out by security forces and the crowd applauded.
   ``Now, who's next?'' the president joked. ``I'm here to talk
about Lynn. This is not a town meeting.''
   A Chicago district police chief, Richard Dwyer, said later the
four protesters were charged with disorderly conduct.
   Later, Bush was bound for Providence, R.I., to raise funds for
Rep. Claudine Schneider, expected to mount a challenge next year to
Sen. Claiborne Pell, a Democratic veteran of 29 years in the Senate.
   He also was helping raise money for Gov. Edward DiPrete, who is
seeking a fourth two-year term in 1990 as Rhode Island's chief
executive.
   Bush said Martin has been in his corner on the fight for a lower
tax on capital gains, which are the profits on the sale of
investments such as real estate or securities.
   ``The capital gains battle may be over for this year, but the
fact is this: we've seen the votes _ a majority in both the Senate
and the House are on record in favor of cutting the capital gains
rate,'' the president said.
   ``When Congress reconvenes in the new year, cutting capital
gains is going to be one of the top items on my agenda. ... It's a
fight we're going to win,'' he said.
   On another topic, Bush said next month's shipboard meeting with
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev off Malta ``will occur
because America has been resolute in defense of liberty.''
   The president began his stop in Chicago by visiting the Pickard
Elementary School classroom of Ana Zamora, a fifth-grader who asked
his help in ridding her neighborhood of drugs.
   ``The pressure is still on out there, so you got to follow
through on what you learn in this school,'' said Bush, who was
accompanied by Illinois Gov. James Thompson, Mayor Richard Daley
and other politicians.
   ``How many of you have ever heard the story about the Little
Train that Could? ... Picard is the little school that could,'' he
said.
   ``All of you have said no to drugs and you've said yes to
education,'' the president said. ``You've refused to be defeated by
marijuana, crack and terrible gang violence.''
   Ana asked Bush ``about how much do you arrest the people'' who
use drugs.
   ``We're beginning to make the case that the user, the person who
uses drugs, has to pay the penalty,'' the president said, urging
the children that ``once you decide you're not going to do it, then
reach out and help somebody else.''
   Asked about the first family's pet dog Millie, the president
said: ``Fine,'' and then disclosed he had taken the dog into the
shower with him the night before.
   ``She rolled in something bad,'' the president told the children.
   After Bush's address to school children in September outlining a
national anti-drug strategy, teachers at Pickard had their pupils
write the president about how drugs affected their lives. A letter
from Ana caught Bush's eye.
   ``I never go outside because my mom gets scared that I'll get
hurt because of the gang fights,'' she wrote. ``President Bush,
I've heard that you're pushing for a war on drugs. Please help
remove drugs from our neighborhood. I will do my part by saying no
to drugs, and I hope you can do yours. I know this is hard, but you
can do it.''
   Martin, Schneider and two other pro-choice GOP congresswomen,
Olympia Snowe of Maine and Nancy Johnson of Connecticut, met with
Bush last Tuesday to urge him to modify his hard-line stance
against abortion funding.
   Bush last month vetoed a major spending bill that would have
allowed Medicaid funding of abortions for rape or incest victims.
   While Bush believes abortion should be legal in those
circumstances, he opposes public funding of abortions except to
save the woman's life.
   Abortion rights became a heated issue in this fall's off-year
elections, with Democrats capturing governorships in Virginia and
New Jersey against Republicans who opposed abortion. When Bush
campaigned in both states Nov. 3, he avoided any mention of his
abortion views.
   Bush said Friday, in an interview with Mutual Radio, ``I know
that our party is big enough to have people in it who differ on
this question.''
   Martin, 49, is a longtime Bush ally who was a national co-chair
of his 1988 campaign.
   She said in an interview she does not think Bush's anti-abortion
stand will hurt Republican candidates.
   ``This is ironic, because just a year and a half ago, people
were asking me, `How can George Bush keep you on as national
co-chair of his campaign when you're pro-choice?''' she said.
   Schneider, 42, is among the most liberal Republicans in
Congress. Pell, who turns 71 on Tuesday, announced last week he
will seek a sixth term.
</TEXT>
