<FIRST>u a AM-Bush-Salvador     11-20 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Salvador,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Defends Salvadoran President, Says Blameless in Killings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Salvador Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Monday defended Salvadoran
President Alfredo Cristiani and his own administration against
suggestions of complicity in the murders of six Jesuit priests in
El Salvador.
   First, Bush told reporters that Cristiani had assured him the
Salvadoran government was not involved in last week's murders.
Then, at a political fund-raiser, the president faced a heckler who
said his administration was killing priests.
   ``We are not. You be quiet,'' Bush shot back.
   His accuser and three other people who also voiced criticism of
U.S. actions regarding El Salvador were led out by security guards
as the crowd applauded.
   Bush went on to say, ``We must not pull our support away from a
freely elected government in Central America.''
   Before leaving for Illinois and Rhode Island on a political trip
for two Republican congresswomen seeking Senate seats, Bush
indicated he might well veto any congressional effort to cut off
aid to the ``fragile democracy.''
   House Democrats did try to put new restrictions on money for El
Salvador, but that effort failed in a 215-194 procedural vote
Monday as the House worked on a broad foreign aid bill Bush vetoed
for different reasons a day earlier.
   There was no effort to cut off aid entirely.
   Bush spoke to reporters as he prepared to board Air Force One at
Andrews Air Force Base in Maryland, near Washington, for the flight
to Chicago.
   He said concerning El Salvador, ``This is no time to undermine a
fragile democracy that is under attack.''
   Bush on Sunday vetoed the foreign aid appropriations bill that
contained money for El Salvador, partly over a provision providing
$15 million for a United Nations agency that funds a Chinese
program that is said to promote abortion as a form of population
control.
   Democratic House leaders decided to open up the bill to a debate
on money for El Salvador, partly in response to speculation by
critics of the Salvadoran government that the murders of six Jesuit
priests were committed by government sympathizers.
   ``In the first place, there is no question, I hope, in the minds
of the American people that we strongly condemn the killings'' last
week of the Jesuit priests ``and apparently the killing of another
priest,'' Bush said.
   Later, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater cited a report ``still not
confirmed that a conservative priest was killed'' in addition to
the six last week.
   ``Here's a freely elected government doing their very best,
trying to protect their population from these Marxist-led
guerrillas coming into the center of the city,'' Bush said. ``And
we support President Cristiani and his effort to restore order.''
   ``This is no time to pull away from President Cristiani,'' Bush
said.
   In their telephone conversation, which he said had taken place
within the past 48 hours, Bush said, ``I told him how strongly we
feel about the killings. And I told him that they must get to the
bottom of it.''
   Bush said he had also offered Cristiani ``technical help in
investigating and bringing to justice'' the murderers.
   Fitzwater said this help would basically consist of
``forensics,'' such as help in fingerprint investigation.
   ``People who did this, whether they come from the extreme left
or the extreme right, (should be) paying the penalty,'' Bush
said.``We cannot condone killing.''
   ``My pitch is this: that we must not pull away from a freely
democratically elected government that had certification of the
freedom of those elections. And to continue to have a handful of
countries ... supporting the outdated concept of Marxist guerillas
is unacceptable to the United States and I must tell the Congress
of the United States that I will not accept as president a cutoff
of aid to El Salavador. That's it.''
   Asked if he believed Cristiani's assurances that his government
was not involved in the killings, Bush said, ``Absolutely. I
believe it. And if some renegade forces were involved on the left
or the right, they should be brought to justice.''
   ``Cristiani would not lie to me on a matter of this nature,''
Bush added.
</TEXT>
