<FIRST>r i AM-India-Singh     11-20 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Singh,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Being Called Next Prime Minister</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-India Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FATEHPUR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hindu priests left their temple, doctors
stopped work at a leper clinic, children cut classes and motorists
left the dusty roads to see the man who may be the next prime
minister.
   Vishwanath Pratap Singh leads a loose-knit coalition of
opposition groups trying to oust Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi and
his Congress Party in parliamentary elections being held Wednesday,
Friday and Sunday.
   Singh, 58, is running for a seat in Fatehpur, which means The
Place of Triumph in Urdu and is 375 miles east of New Delhi on the
holy Ganges River.
   His 25-vehicle caravan traveled 60 miles of poor roads to reach
voters in remote villages, stopping about every three miles so
Singh could speak to supporters.
   ``My winning is not an issue here,'' he said at one village.
``The issue is the defeat of the Congress Party, the eradication of
corruption.''
   Polls indicate the National Front coalition may oust Gandhi and
the Congress Party and make Singh, once Gandhi's most-trusted
minister, India's next leader.
   The opposition accuses the government of high-level corruption,
alleging the Swedish arms manufacturer Bofors paid as much as $50
million in kickbacks to get a $1.4 billion army artillery contract.
   Gandhi has denied the accusation, but his government's
popularity has suffered severaly.
   ``There is no doubt that we are going to win,'' Singh said,
waving to children who had left school to see him.
   Many people in Fatehpur see him as a crusader against corruption.
   ``He is the best man to become the prime minister,'' said Abdul
Jabbar, a 70-year-old priest.
   ``Fatehpur will have a prime minister now,'' said Rabhubir
Singh, a 55-year-old farmer not related to the candidate. ``He is
another avtar,'' incarnation of God.
   Many residents have begun calling Singh the ``pradhan mantri,''
or prime minister, and he does not discourage them.
   ``This is a people's wave,'' he said at a rally of about 1,000
people near a Hindu temple at Kurai. ``It is the people's wish that
corrupt politicians should go.''
   At the end of the day, a procession of supporters chanted in
unison, ``He is not king, but a saint!''
   Singh smiled, his hands outstretched.
</TEXT>
