<DOCNO> AP891120-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 1519EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Prison-AIDS     11-20 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prison-AIDS,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS Victim Ordered Out of Federal Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal prison inmate suffering from AIDS was on
his way to a private hospital Monday after a judge ruled the U.S.
Bureau of Prisons lacks adequate facilities to treat the disease.
   Lawyers in the case of Leonardo Botero Gomez, 43, said Monday
they are preparing a class-action lawsuit on behalf of all federal
prisoners with AIDS.
   ``This is a precedent-setting case putting the Bureau of Prisons
on trial for their callous disregard of prisoners' serious health
care needs,'' said attorney David Tucker, who represented Gomez.
   It is the first time a sentenced federal prisoner has been freed
on bond for medical treatment, said Tucker's associate, Benson
Weintraub.
   In Washington, Bureau of Prisons spokesmen Greg Bogdan said the
agency was conferring with its counsel and seeking more information
before responding publicly to the ruling. He initially said there
was not a large number of federal inmates with AIDS, but later said
the agency would not comment on that subject.
   Gomez, sentenced May 5 to a minimum 10 years for cocaine
trafficking, is in the most advanced stage of AIDS and has a life
expectancy of 24 months or less, Weintraub said.
   On Monday, the inmate was en route to an undisclosed hospital
for treatment, the lawyer said.
   U.S. District Judge Eugene Spellman ordered Gomez freed Friday
on $250,000 bond pending a full civil trial, scheduled for January.
The inmate was released later in the day after Spellman's order was
upheld by the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta.
   Spellman heard testimony that Gomez, who is taking the anti-AIDS
drug AZT, was being treated at the infirmary of the federal
Metropolitan Correctional Center near Miami. About every four weeks
he was sent to the AIDS treatment center at Miami's public Jackson
Memorial Hospital.
   ``The treatment lacks the quality of continuity which is
considered necessary in treating an illness of this nature,''
Spellman wrote in his decision.
   The judge also said the prison lacks some of the drugs necessary
to prolong Gomez's life, and found that the prison doctor had seen
Gomez only twice in the previous two weeks.
   ``The care available to (Gomez) does not meet the requirements
of the law,'' Spellman ruled.
   The U.S. Attorney's office, which sought unsuccessfully to keep
Gomez in prison pending trial, refused comment on the case.
   The Bureau of Prisons runs an AIDS treatment center in
Springfield, Mo.
</TEXT>
