<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 1534EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Press     11-20 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Press,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Striking Newspaper Workers Lose Court Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspaper workers lost a court battle Monday in
their bid to restore their chief editor, who was fired after
publishing remarks by a controversial parliamentarian.
   A regional court declared illegal a strike by workers at the
Banner of Communism newspaper in Noginsk, a city east of Moscow.
The court said that if the workers don't return to their jobs
Tuesday, they will be fired or fined.
   The controversy began last month, when the newspaper published a
speech by Yuri N. Afanasyev to the Interregional Deputies Group, an
organization of opposition members of the Congress of People's
Deputies to which he and maverick Communist Boris N. Yeltsin belong.
   The contents of the speech were not known, but Afanasyev has
challenged the very underpinnings of the Soviet state, saying the
official ideology of Marxism-Leninism is outmoded.
   The newspaper's publishers, the city government and Communist
Party officials in Noginsk, Afanasyev's home district, fired the
editor-in-chief of Banner of Communism on Oct. 25. The officials
accused editor Vladimir Puchkov of being ``ideologically
irresponsible,'' the weekly Moscow News reported.
   A mass rally in defense of the newspaper was held three days
later, and its workers went on strike Nov. 3 to press for Puchkov's
reinstatement.
   The city took the strikers to court, and supporters packed the
Moscow courtroom for Monday's hearing, brandishing slogans such as
``Let's Defend the Freedom of the Press'' and ``Hands Off
Free-Thinking Editors.''
   Defense lawyer Andrei Makarov contended the strike was purely
political and legal, particularly because a parliamentary decree
says the press should give priority to publishing materials by its
local parliamentarians.
   Afanasyev testified the case was a ``symptom of the curbing of
glasnost, a symptom of opposition to the course defined by the
Communist Party.'' He said the court action stemmed from President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's criticism of him and other outspoken
practitioners of glasnost in a meeting with editors last month.
   Referring to the Interregional Deputies Group, the Soviet leader
reportedly accused Afanasyev and two economists of joining with
Yeltsin to form ``a fascist clique striving for power.'' Informed
Soviet sources said Gorbachev told the meeting Afanasyev should be
expelled from the Communist Party.
   Afanasyev, the 55-year-old head of the Moscow State Historical
Archives Institute, came under repeated attack in the state-run
press after Gorbachev's remarks.
   The Communist Party daily Pravda quoted Afanasyev as saying the
party has no authority and has led the country nowhere. Pravda said
Afanasyev, who appears frequently at rallies by unofficial
political groups and speaks in a booming baritone, never backs up
his charges with proof and has turned from historian to priest. In
another article, the newspaper quoted him as saying perestroika
marks the end of the last empire, the Soviet Union.
   He shot to fame in a nationally televised speech in May to the
Congress. With Gorbachev looking on, Afanasyev said the Soviet
leader had either listened to, or influenced an ``aggressively
obedient majority'' in the Congress to elect a
``Brezhnevist-Stalinist'' legislature.
</TEXT>
