<FIRST>r w AM-RuralHealth     11-20 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rural Health,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rural Emergency Services Plagued by Lack of Resources, Personnel</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release 6:30 p.m. EST; time set by source.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emergency medical services in many rural areas
are plagued by personnel shortages, inadequate training, out-dated
equipment and lack of financial and medical resources, according to
a report released Monday.
   The very nature of rural areas, where residents often live many
miles from a hospital, creates special problems that can delay
emergency services, which sometimes results in death or permanent
injury, the Office of Technology Assessment, a congressional
research office, said in its report.
   More federal money and better state planning could ease some of
the problems that affect the health care of the one-quarter of the
U.S. population that lives outside the nation's metropolitan areas,
the report said.
   The extent and quality of emergency medical services vary from
state to state. For example, Hawaii spent nearly $14 per capita on
such services in 1988, while Ohio spent 2 cents for each resident,
according to the report.
   Federal funds for emergency medical services reached about $30
million annually after passage of the 1973 EMS Systems Act, but
began to decline in 1981 when the money was folded into block grant
programs.
   In 1988, about $18 million in federal funds went to the states
for emergency medical services.
   The report argues for an increased federal role in providing
these services to rural areas, but doesn't say how much additional
funds would be necessary.
   Among the options the report lists are increased federal funds
for training and continuing education for emergency medical service
personnel and more federally funded research and demonstration
programs to address problems unique to rural areas.
   The report also suggests development of national guidelines or
standards for emergency medical service providers and specialized
facilities such as trauma centers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
