<SECOND>PM-Chinese Students, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0508,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>House OKs Bill To Aid Chinese Students</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs `The bill, ...' with 1 graf to CORRECT day
to Sunday, sted Friday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has unanimously approved a bill that
would give students from China the opportunity to remain in the
United States rather than face possible political persecution back
home.
   The bill, a reaction to the oppression of students demonstrators
by the Beijing government, cleared the House 403-0 late Sunday and
was sent to the Senate, which has yet to act.
   President Bush is expected to sign the legislation.
   The legislation waives the requirement that holders of exchange
visitor visas, known as J visas, return home for at least two years
before applying to the U.S. government for a change in their visa
status.
   About four-fifths of the 40,000 Chinese students in the United
States hold that type of visa. They would be required to file for a
change in visa status within four years of enactment of the bill,
or return to China.
   The bill also requires the Justice Department to give special
consideration to Chinese nationals who seek asylum status in the
United States because of China's population control policy of only
allowing one child per family.
</TEXT>
