<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--TimesSquareBall     11-20 0146</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Times Square Ball,0147</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Ads on the Ball, Building Owner Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man in charge of the ball that drops in
Times Square on New Year's Eve said Monday there is no truth to
reports he was considering turning the shining sphere into a
sliding billboard.
   New York magazine, quoting an unidentified source, said a
soft-drink company was negotiating to put an advertisement on the
ball.
   Not true, said Steven Israel, owner of One Times Square, the
building millions stare at in the waning seconds of each year. Last
year he got rid of the tourism-touting ``Big Apple'' that was used
for several years, and brought back the classic ball.
   ``I think it's a great American tradition,'' Israel said. ``I
fought hard to keep that tradition by bringing back the old ball,
and I'll make sure it stays that way.''
</TEXT>
