<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 1702EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Walesa     11-20 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Walesa,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa, in Latin America, Pledges Solidarity in Solving Common Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY CAPLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa arrived
Monday after a successful U.S. tour, pledging that Eastern Europe
and Latin America would work together in improving their
debt-ridden economies.
   Sporting a U.S. Congressional tie clasp and a medallion of
Poland's Black Madonna, Walesa was greeted by hundreds of labor
leaders and members of the Polish community as he landed at
Venezuela's Simon Bolivar International Airport on a private
chartered flight.
   Walesa was in Venezuela to attend a world labor summit called by
the World Confederation of Labor, a 50 million-member organization
to which his Solidarity trade union is affiliated.
   Enthusiastic reporters broke through a cordon as Walesa
descended on the tarmac and surrounded the jovial union man who
thrilled crowds on his U.S. tour.
   ``Do not fear. Walesa is here to be with you, to serve you and
not to govern you,'' Walesa said, speaking through an interpreter.
   Walesa said Poland and Latin America shared common interests in
fighting for solutions to their foreign debt burdens.
   ``The debt is like a man with swollen feet who cannot put his
shoes on. It is impossible to move forward,'' said Walesa.
   Poland owes foreign banks $38 billion, while Venezuela, the
fourth-largest Latin American debtor, owes $34 billion to banks,
mostly in the United States. The total Third World debt stands at
$1.3 trillion.
   Asked whether possible U.S. aid to troubled Eastern Europe would
mean less funds available for Latin America and Africa, Walesa
pledged international solidarity in solving the global crisis.
   ``It is a poor militant who cannot recognize the necessity in a
brother. Latin America has a moral imperative to receive aid
because of past exploitation,'' said Walesa.
   Walesa said solutions would come when developing nations, like
Eastern Europe, improved the efficiency of their economies.
   ``But not at the cost of the worker. The unions must fight for
all they can. They must be strong,'' Walesa said.
   ``But they must not strangle the system in which they operate,''
he added.
   Walesa said he had no political ambitions in Poland, where a
coalition he helped form three months ago ousted a hard-line
Communist regime.
   He compared himself to an ``anti-hero,'' saying he was willing
to serve, but did not expect any honors from it.
   Walesa was scheduled to stay in Venezuela for three days to
attend the labor summit and meet Venezuelan political leaders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891120-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 1626EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-BabySwap     11-20 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baby Swap,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legal Battle Looms in Baby Swap Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two families tried in separate ways Monday
to deal with the knowledge they raised each other's child, and a
legal battle loomed against a hospital their lawyers blame for
switching newborns.
   Relatives said Robert Mays was in seclusion with Kimberly, the
girl he's raised since birth more than 10 years ago and just
discovered isn't his real daughter.
   Kimberly Michelle Mays is really the child of Ernest and Regina
Twigg, according to the results of genetic blood tests made public
Sunday. Attorneys for both families say the tests also showed that
Arlena, the daughter the Twiggs reared, was born to Mays and his
late wife, Barbara, who died of cancer in 1981.
   Arlena died of heart disease last year.
   When Mays was told Sunday that his only biological child had
died, the first thing he asked was the site of her grave, said his
attorney, Arthur Ginsburg.
   Mays was expected to return to Sarasota on Tuesday and attend a
news conference Wednesday at his attorney's office, legal assistant
Judy Lee said.
   The parents say the girls were born just a few days apart in
late November and early December 1978 at Hardee Memorial Hospital
in Wauchula in rural central Florida.
   With results of the genetic tests, the Twiggs' lawyer, John
Blakely, said he will press the hospital harder for information
about how the babies were switched.
   ``The Hardee Memorial Hospital has been uncooperative in helping
us solve this tragedy,'' Blakely said. ``It's been a real tragedy
for the two families and hopefully we will find out how it
happened.''
   Blakely has filed a federal suit against Hardee Memorial
alleging employees switched the Twiggs' newborn for a sickly child
through negligence, medical malpractice or deliberate acts.
   Ginsburg said Mays also might sue.
   ``It was either a terribly negligent act or somebody's done
something deliberately that's hurt a lot of people,'' the lawyer
said. ``There isn't any fair amount of money to compensate them for
what they've gone through and what they're going to go through.''
   Harrell Connelly, administrator of Hardee Memorial, was
unavailable for comment Monday; the hospital switchboard would only
take messages and calls were not returned. Janet Adams of Orlando,
the hospital's lawyer, didn't immediately return calls.
   The battle over Kimberly was the outgrowth of the Arlena's fatal
heart condition. Blood tests revealed she wasn't related to either
of the Twiggs. After her death, the couple began a 14-month search
for the child they lost.
   So far, they have only seen pictures of the slender, hazel-eyed
Kimberly. The next step is for psychologists to interview the girl
and draw up plans for a first meeting and a schedule for visitation.
   To get Mays to agree to genetic testing, the Twiggs agreed not
to seek custody. They say they'll be satisfied with visitation
privileges.
   ``After we consulted with some psychologists, we determined that
it would most likely be in Kimberly's best interest to stay with
Mr. Mays,'' Blakely said Monday during an appearance with the
couple on ``CBS This Morning.''
   ``We're trying to work it out so Kimberly can be a real winner
in this matter. She can maintain her loving relationship with the
man who she has thought to be her father while simultaneously she
can get two new loving parents, additional parents,'' he said.
   Ginsburg said he hadn't talked to Mays since giving him the test
results, and didn't know how Kimberly reacted.
   ``Kimberly is our granddaughter. She is still our
granddaughter,'' Merle Coker, the man Kimberly calls Grandpa, said
Monday. ``We're doing fine. We'll survive. We'll play it by ear.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
