<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 1944EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Romania     11-20 0151</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia-Romania,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>Romania Closes its Border With Yugoslavia, Tanjug Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Romania, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania has closed its border with
Yugoslavia and turned back all travelers, the Tanjug news agency
reported Monday.
   Yugoslav companies that have offices in Bucharest, Romania's
capital, were officially informed their staff would not be allowed
to enter Romania during the Communist Party congress that opened
Monday, Tanjug said.
   Sunday's move came without warning, Tanjug said.
   All tourists arriving at the border from Yugoslavia were turned
back without any explanation, the news agency reported.
   On Sunday, the Romanian foreign ministry barred Dragoslav
Markovic, a Tanjug correspondent who specialized in Romanian
affairs, from traveling to Bucharest to report on the congress.
Other journalists were held up for several hours at the border by
Romanian police.
   Hungarian state radio reported Friday that Romania severely
curbed border-crossing traffic but restrictions were reportedly
relaxed somewhat by Sunday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
