<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 1708EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Economy     11-20 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Economy,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Lawmakers Give Preliminary OK to Emergency Economic Measure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The national legislature gave preliminary approval
Monday to an emergency economic package that imposes new price
controls and bans the export of scarce goods in a bid to stop the
slide in the Soviet standard of living.
   The official news agency Tass said the Supreme Soviet took the
action in an attempt to help retirees and other low-income groups
that are hard-pressed by price increases and the widespread
shortage of basic goods and supplies.
   The measure bans price increases for several commodities, as
well as clothes and shoes, and places a quota on the export of such
scarce items as fish products, fur and electric appliances.
   Tass said many Soviet businesses have been exporting these
items, rather than make them available to the domestic economy, in
order to obtain coveted foreign currency.
   The measure, which is to be presented to the 2,250-member
Congress of People's Deputies during next session, which begins
Dec. 12, also enables the state to order production of inexpensive
items for retirees and children that businesses have stopped
manufacturing because they are not profitable.
   Deputy Premier Leonid I. Abalkin, President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's chief economist, proposed the measures a week after a
conference of academics and economic managers recommended
longer-term fixes for the Soviet economy. The conference suggested
measured price increases, dumping unprofitable state businesses,
expanding forms of ownership and development of a stock market.
</TEXT>
