<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 1958EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NBC-Re-enactments     11-20 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NBC-Re-enactments,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC News Ends News Recreations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Everette in 2nd-to-last graf is correct</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC News, finding the use of news recreations in
its ``Yesterday, Today &amp; Tomorrow'' specials too confusing to
viewers, said Monday it won't use the technique anymore. It won't
keep the show, either.
   No NBC News staff members will continue on the show, including
its anchor team of Mary Alice Williams, Maria Shriver and Chuck
Scarborough, said Tom Ross, a senior vice president at NBC News.
   Three YTT specials have aired, the first on Aug. 2. A fourth,
made by NBC News and with a news event re-enactment by actors, will
air on Nov. 28. After that, NBC said, the YTT concept will go to
NBC Entertainment for further development.
   Once considered a candidate to be NBC's only prime time news
series, YTT was the only NBC News show on which recreations were
used. CBS News' low-rated ``Saturday Night With Connie Chung''
series still uses them. No ABC News series does or will, ABC News
president Roone Arledge has said.
   NBC News president Michael Gartner, asked if the use of news
recreations in network news programs is on the way out, had a
prompt reply.
   ``It is at NBC,'' he said. ``It was an experiment. We're proud
of what we did. For reasons of clarity, however, we won't be doing
them any longer.''
   Those who use recreations on the CBS and NBC programs defend
them as accurate and well-sourced. But the technique, which dates
to network radio days, has been criticized in recent months by such
traditionalists as former CBS News president Richard Salant.
   They argue that news recreations, among other things, confuse
viewers about what is real and what is recreated with actors
playing actual people.
   The YTT recreations, while overseen by NBC News, were made in
Los Angeles by Cosgrove-Meurer Productions, which makes the NBC
entertainment series ``Unsolved Mysteries.''
   In a statement announcing the change, Gartner agreed with the
critics' contentions, saying that ``we have determined that the
practice can result in confusion to the viewers.''
   He also said YTT experimented with other new techniques that may
be incorporated in the new prime-time news series that Jane Pauley
will anchor next summer. Pauley is leaving as ``Today'' co-anchor
in January.
   In an interview, Gartner said that while all of YTT's
recreations were done responsibly, ``there still seemed to be some
confusion ... everytime you said `recreation,' it sort of set off a
little alarm in the viewer's mind.
   ``So I decided that the only way that NBC could deal with it is
to just say, `There are no recreations on NBC (News).' And that
removes all doubt and confusion.''
   ``Well, hooray ... this is good news,'' Salant said of Gartner's
decision.
   CBS News spokesman Tom Goodman said there was no truth to
reports Chung's CBS show would drop news recreations.
   ``We're doing a mix of features, interviews, and segments with
reconstructions,'' Goodman said. ``We'll continue to do them
(recreations) and other things as well.''
   Saturday's Chung show has no news recreations, he said. Of nine
shows broadcast to date, three had no recreations, four had
recreation segments, and two consisted entirely of a recreated news
story, he said.
   Everette Dennis, executive director of the Gannett Center for
Media Studies, has said he's not disturbed by responsible network
news recreations. He expressed reservations Monday about NBC's
decision to drop them.
   ``I would frankly rather have seen recreations develop and
mature as a legitimate news tool, rather than simply be relegated
back to the entertainment division,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891120-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 2000EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Doctor-Salvador     11-20 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Doctor-Salvador,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Recalls Night of Arrest in El Salvador</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American physician who was arrested and
held overnight in connection with her work at a Lutheran Church
clinic in San Salvador said Monday her ordeal ``was nothing
compared to what the Salvadoran people have suffered.''
   Asked at a news conference whether she would return to El
Salvador after her experience in the country's capital last week,
Dr. Paula Brentlinger said, ``Until conditions exist that would
permit me to work as a physician, I am not sure what the point
would be.''
   ``If I were to go back now, I think I'd be in hiding with a lot
of other people because it was made very clear to me that I would
not be permitted ... to work,'' the family doctor from Seattle said.
   She was detained along with 11 foreign health professionals and
lay church workers and three Salvadorans last Thursday. They were
taken to Treasury Police headquarters, where they were questioned,
held overnight and then released.
   ``The sick and wounded still lie unattended in the battle zones
of the capital,'' she said. ``The Geneva Conventions _ despite the
pleas of the Red Cross, the churches, and even the guerrilla forces
_ are not being respected. What I went through was nothing compared
to what the Salvadoran people have suffered in the last ten years,
and ten days, of the war.''
   The doctor, who said she was raised as a congregationalist, has
worked periodically since 1986 as a volunteer physician with the
Lutheran Church of El Salvador. Since September, she has been
treating patients at several sites in San Salvador. Before that,
she was with the Pacific Medical Center in Seattle.
   Physicians for Human Rights, an organization of health
professionals that sponsored her press conference here, said she
was returning to Seattle to continue her practice of medicine.
   The doctor gave this account of her arrest:
   ``At around 4 p.m. on Nov. 16, as I was preparing to examine a
woman in labor, armed and uniformed members of the Salvadoran
National Guard came into the building in which we were working.
They demanded to see the passports of all the foreigners in the
building. After we handed over our documents, the guardsmen loaded
us into a pickup truck and took us to their headqaurters.''
   She said they were blindfolded and driven somewhere within the
police headquarters, where they were handcuffed.
   ``Treasury policemen shouted to each other that we were the
foreigners who had been providing medical attention to wounded
guerrilla combatants,'' she said. ``I was eventually taken from my
cell _ where I had been forced to stand, blindfolded and handcuffed
_ by a Treasury policeman who partly removed my blindfold and then
yelled in my ear that I should tell him how many guerrillas I had
taken care of at the Lutheran clinic.''
   The doctor, who told reporters that the clinic did not ask for
the political affiliation of patients and would treat the wounded
of either side, said she was attempting to answer this question
when another policeman entered the room, asked her name and told
her interrogator to remove the handcuffs.
   ``At this point the interrogation became fairly courteous, and
my blindfold and handcuffs were removed,'' she said. ``I spend most
of the night alone in a cell.''
   Late the next morning, the U.S. citizens in the group were
released to representatives of the U.S. Embassy in San Salvador.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891120-0121 </DOCNO>
