<FIRST>r w AM-CentennialCoins     11-20 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Centennial Coins,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>House OKs Commemorative Dollars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One million silver dollars would be minted to
commemorate 100 years of statehood for Idaho, Montana, Washington,
Wyoming and the Dakotas, under legislation approved Monday by the
House.
   A similar measure already passed the Senate. Differences between
the two bills will be worked out by a conference committee.
   ``In the minting of this coin, we are recognizing the importance
of silver to all the states involved, both historically and
economically,'' said Rep. Pat Williams, D-Mont., before the House
passed on voice vote the bill he co-sponsored.
   The six states entered the union in 1889 and 1890.
   Williams noted that one of the largest silver deposits ever
discovered was in Montana.
   ``The centennial coins and silver proof sets will also provide a
helpful boost to the regional mining recovery now under way,'' said
Rep. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, who also co-sponsored the measure.
   The coins will contain 90 percent silver and 10 percent alloy.
Each coin will be sold for $20 to $25.
   The bill also authorizes production of a mint set that would be
more than 99 percent silver.
   The House's original bill called for the minting of 350,000
five-dollar palladium coins, but the scarcity of the precious metal
caused the body to drop that provision before passing the measure.
   Further study is being conducted, however, and Williams said the
conference committee might find a way to include the minting of
some palladium coins in the legislation.
   A five-dollar palladium coin would be sold for more than $300,
an aide to Williams estimated.
   The secretary of the treasury would decide on the design for the
coins after consultation with the Commission on Fine Arts,
according to the bill.
   Profits from selling the coins would help reduce the national
debt and to pay for a traveling exhibit of historic documents
relating to each state's course toward statehood.
   The coins would be sold by the Treasury Department at outlets,
mostly banks, throughout the country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891120-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 1727EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-SpaceExploration     11-20 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Exploration,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Team Proposes Return To Moon And Man On Mars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A NASA team has fleshed out President Bush's
visions of American outposts on the moon and Mars with a script
that would have four humans arriving on the red planet in 2011, and
returning for a 600-day stay in 2018.
   The study, delivered to the National Space Council, does not
contain any estimates of cost, but Director Richard Darman of the
Office of Management and Budget has put the price tag of going to
Mars in the $400 billion range.
   The report envisions space station Freedom, which is scheduled
to be completed in 1999, becoming ``a transportation node where
both lunar and Mars vehicles will be assembled, tested, launched
and refurbished to fly again.''
   The report was commissioned by NASA administrator Richard Truly
to provide a database for the National Space Council as it
considers approaches for meeting the president's goals.
   ``We will not stop at the moon,'' the report said, ``because the
imperative to explore will lead men and women to Mars. The planet
most like earth, Mars offers many unique scientific opportunities,
but perhaps the most intriguing question is whether life exeists or
has ever existed on Mars.''
   Life may exist on Mars today, the study said, ``in underground
habitats where volcanic heating melts ground ice, producing a warm,
wet environment protected from harsh surface conditions.''
   Five approaches for meeting Bush's goals are laid out.
   Approach A would establish a human presence on the moon in 2001,
permanently occupying it in 2002 and leveling off development of
the outpost in 2012 in order to finance start of a Mars expedition,
arriving in 2016.
   Approach B would delay some of the science activities on both
moon and Mars in order to advance the Martian arrival to 2011.
   Approaches C and D would alter the timelines somewhat, the
latter delaying milestones by 2 to 3 years.
   Under Approach E, activities on the moon would be cut back to
only one mission a year. Humans would return to the moon, one
flight a year beginning in 2004, for tours of duty ranging from 30
days to 6 months. In this scenario, the first crew of four would
arrive on Mars in 2016.
   Any such large-scale endeavors, the report says, requires launch
vehicles with much greater capacity to lift heavy payloads:
``approximately 60 metric tons (132,000 pounds) for the lunar
outpost, and about 140 metric tons (309,000 pounds) for the Mars
outpost.
   The shuttle's cargo capacity, ordered to be lowered as one
result of the Challenger accident, is 38,000 pounds.
   The report said its planning for human exploration of the solar
system has concentrated on use of high performance engines and a
technique called aerobraking where the atmosphere of planet is used
to decelerate a spacecraft and change its trajectory.
   The study recommends consideringh nuclear propulsion as a major
alternative.
   ``No significant United States program is investigating the
potential of nuclear thermal rocket propulsion for exploration
missions,'' the report said. ``Facilities for testing nuclear
thermal rocket systems is a major issue that must be resolved in
order to make development of this extremely effective technology
possible.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
