<FIRST>u w AM-US-Czechoslovakia     11-20 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Czechoslovakia,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>US Calls In Envoy To Protest Roughing Up Of Demonstrators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Monday canceled a
visit by a high-level official from Czechoslovakia and condemned
the use of force by police against peaceful demonstrators in Prague.
   ``We're disappointed,'' Richard Schifter, the head of the
department's human rights office, told Ambassador Miroslav
Houstecky, who was handed a 600-word statement of sharp U.S.
disapproval.
   Earlier, Margaret D. Tutwiler, the department's spokeswoman,
said the police actions were ``in sharp contrast to other East
European countries who are beginning to respond to the wishes of
their people.''
   She said authorities in Prague had damaged Czechoslovakia's
credibility at home and abroad.
   Ambassador Houstecky was simultanteously called to Schifter's
office to receive an official protest. While he probably assumed it
was coming, the envoy apparently was taken by surprise by the
cancellation of a planned visit by Jan Fojtik, the Czechoslovakian
Communist Party ideology chief.
   His visit later this month was to mark a general improvement in
U.S. relations with the communist government. Secretary of State
James A. Baker III met in September in New York with Foreign
Minister Jaromir Johanes. It was the first session at that high a
level in 11 years. Lower-level officials subsequently held other
meetings.
   Schifter reminded Houstecky that Czechoslovakia's poor human
rights record was the major barrier between the two countries and
that ``we were going to engage at high levels to overcome that
barrier,'' Nat Kingsley, a department press officer, said.
   ``Because of of recent violent attacks, we are canceling the
invitation,'' the U.S. human rights chief said. ``The
Czechoslovakian government has totally ignored the basic thrust of
the dialogue begun in a sincere atmosphere in New York.''
   The ambassador did not respond directly, although he was clearly
aware of what was going on in Prague, Kingsley said. ``He talked
about a need to move forward without chaos,'' the U.S. official
said.
   The protest statement said the Czechoslovakian government ``has
made a mockery'' of the dialogue begun in New York. ``We are even
more disappointed that the Czechoslovak government has demonstrated
so violently its unwillingness to address its citizens' hopes for
democracy,'' it said.
   Ending on a hopeful note, the statement said, ``For the sake of
the people of Czechoslovakia, who have known democracy and freedom
and who have suffered so obviously, the United States government
hopes the government of Czechoslovakia will promptly reconsider its
policies. ...'
</TEXT>
