<FIRST>u w AM-Pentagon-BudgetCuts 1stLd-Writethru   11-20 0796</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon-Budget Cuts, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0622,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Looking at $20 Billion Cut for 1991</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf pvs `Another senior ...' with 1 graf to DELETE
reference to percentage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, spurred by
reforms in Eastern Europe and fiscal pressures at home, on Monday
analyzed ``worst-case scenario'' budget cuts that could include a
$20 billion slash in projected spending for the 1991 fiscal year,
sources said.
   Cheney, in more than four hours of conferences with the
Pentagon's civilian leadership, the chiefs of the Army, Navy and
Air Force, and Joint Chiefs Chairman Gen. Colin Powell, also
reviewed the military's suggestions for dealing with his orders to
cut spending by $180 billion between 1992-'94, other sources said.
   The long-range cutbacks are thought to be the most painful
considered by Pentagon leaders since the end of the Vietnam War.
   They envision possibly closing as many as 15 Air Force bases;
cutting back five Air Force fighter wings; stretching out the
purchase of the B-2 stealth bomber; mothballing the Navy's four
battleships and at least two carriers; and eliminating up to four
Army divisions, said one Pentagon official who spoke privately.
   Pentagon spokesman Pete Williams said Cheney had not made any
decisions about the reported suggestions.
   ``This is a worst-case scenario,'' Williams said, adding that
the secretary wants the services to conduct the ``budget exercise''
to be ready to respond, given the changes occurring under Soviet
leader Mikhail Gorbachev and the budget pressures of the nation's
deficit.
   ``In a dynamic era, you have to have a dynamic process and plan
accordingly,'' Williams said.
   ``There is real pain when you cut the defense budget,'' he said.
``The question is, how much pain can you take and still ensure the
nation's security?''
   Over the weekend, Congress approved a $286 billion defense
budget for the 1990 fiscal year that began Oct. 1.
   Another senior Pentagon official, who spoke on condition he not
be identified by name, said Cheney is negotiating with Budget
Director Richard Darmen on plans for a possible spending cut for
the 1991 fiscal year, or about $20 billion in cuts from the
projected $317 billion _ a revised figured settled on earlier this
year that takes inflation into account.
   ``It could be that bad,'' the official said. ``It could be, that
we have to cut that much.''
   The Pentagon expects to have its 1991 spending projection
submitted to the Office of Management and Budget by Dec. 8, the
official said.
   Cheney ordered the armed services last week to come up with the
$180 billion in spending cuts, but didn't direct how the cuts
should be made.
   The service chiefs reported back to him Monday with details
about how they would function in the coming years if such cuts had
to be made, another Pentagon official said.
   ``These are very significant cuts that we are talking about _
and Congress is going to have to be made aware that there is a
price to be paid when we talk about a smaller defense budget. This
is going to affect the folks here and the folks out there'' in the
various states, the official said.
   In a rare confluence of budget planning discussions, Williams
said, Pentagon officials are juggling questions dealing with budget
uncertainties for the current fiscal year, demands to produce
budget plans for the upcoming fiscal year by early December and at
the same time produce long-term budget projections for up to 1994.
   Williams said it was clear to the Pentagon leadership that
President Bush's earlier projections for 1 percent spending
increases for fiscal 1991 and 1992, followed by 2 percent increases
in 1993 and 1994 aren't realistic anymore.
   ``We know we won't get $317 billion for 1991. But if we sat
here, dumb, fat and happpy, and didn't plan for the future, and
went along as if nothing had changed, Congress would be howling,
`Don't they see the deficit? Don't they see the world has changed?'
The message has gone out _ we are looking for realistic goals,''
Williams said.
   Cheney has ``no intention of going up to Capitol Hill and having
his budget thrown back in his face,'' Williams said. ``This is
going to be a very painful process for everyone.''
   Williams denied that if the Pentagon plans for budget cuts it
might weaken Bush's hand at the upcoming summit with Gorbachev.
   ``This is a planning process, and we have to take a long look
down the road,'' he said.
   ``We won't do anything unilaterally, and a whole lot `ifs' must
be answered. These things can happen _ if the conventional force
talks in Vienna are successful, if the strategic arms talks are
successful, if the Soviets stop their meddling in the Third World.''
</TEXT>
