<FIRST>r w AM-FDA-InterimCommissioner     11-20 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FDA-Interim Commissioner,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Benson to Serve As Interim FDA Commissioner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James S. Benson, acting deputy commissioner of
the Food and Drug Administration, will serve as interim
commissioner when the agency's current chief leaves next month,
officials announced Monday.
   FDA Commissioner Frank Young is to leave the post Dec. 18 to
become a deputy assistant secretary for health in the Department of
Health and Human Services. FDA is also part of the department.
   HHS Secretary Louis Sullivan said Benson ``will assure
continuity and strong, professional leadership'' at FDA, which was
rocked earlier this year by a generic drug scandal that has led to
several bribery convictions and dozens of recalls.
   ``He will assure that the vigorous initiatives in progress under
Dr. Young will continue uninterrupted,'' while a search is
conducted for a permanent commissioner, Sullivan said.
   Benson, in a statement, said he was honored by the appointment,
adding, ``I shall do everything in my power to keep the FDA moving
forward.''
   Unlike Young and the commissioners before him who were appointed
by the department secretary, the next FDA chief will be appointed
by the president and confirmed by the Senate. The change was made
in a law passed by Congress last year.
   The FDA is the federal agency responsible for assuring the
safety of drugs, cosmetics, medical devices, radiological products
and most food products.
</TEXT>
