<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Leipzig 1stLd-Writethru a0634 11-20 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Leipzig, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0634,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Reform March Draws 200,000, Denounces Communist Leaders</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to include higher crowd estimate, other demos.
Picks up 3rd graf pvs, `Young and ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEIPZIG, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 200,000 people chanting
``Freedom! Freedom!'' marched Monday night for free elections and
removal of the nation's Communist leaders.
   ADN, the official news agency, said 100,000 demonstrated in
Dresden, 50,000 each in Karl-Marx-Stadt and Halle; and 10,000 in
Schwerin.
   Activists backing New Forum and other opposition groups pressing
for more democratic change criticized what one speaker called the
``chaos'' wrought by 40 years of communism.
   Young and old braved freezing temperatures to attend the latest
of the now regular weekly rallies after prayer services in Leipzig,
the hotbed of protest in East Germany's recent turmoil.
   From a balcony at Leipzig's opera house, speakers denounced past
rigid practices and demanded justice from the leaders who
mishandled the economy.
   Hans-Joachim Schulz, who said he had no party affiliation, drew
cheers when he accused the ruling Communist Party of ``lying and
deceiving us'' and leading the country into catastrophe.
   ``It has lost the confidence of the people,'' Schulz said of the
party.
   He voiced skepticism about the Communists' new reformist image,
saying, ``a snake sheds its skin, but it doesn't change.''
   Another speaker criticized official corruption and the party's
steadfast refusal to bend to the reform wave until mass protests
and an exodus of East Germans to the West swelled to proportions
that could no longer be ignored.
   A speaker for New Forum called for a wholesale reform of
socialism and rejected calls for reunification with capitalist West
Germany.
   ``The fences and walls must fall, but we do not want to become
the poorhouse of greater Germany,'' said the speaker, who did not
give his name.
   The demonstrators observed a moment of silence in honor of the
Czechoslovak demonstrators brutally dispersed from pro-democracy
protests in Prague in recent days. About 100,000 again marched on
the Czechoslovak capital on Monday.
   East Germany's ADN news agency reported the Leipzig
demonstration and noted the calls for the Communists to step down.
   The agency also noted placards and banners calling on East
Germans to renounce black-market currency trades that further
damage the economy.
   One placard showed a Mercedes-Benz symbol with claws
figuratively reaching for East Germany, with the words ``No
thanks'' to the lure of the West.
   ``The whole world laughs at visas without money,'' declared
another.
   Heiko Brandt, a student, called for the resignation of the
government and said officials should be made to account for
mistakes ``with due severity.''
</TEXT>
