<FIRST>r a AM-SpaceShuttle 1stLd-Writethru a0541 11-20 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0541,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Countdown Progresses Toward Thanksgiving Eve Space Shuttle Launch</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd, `Workers were ..., to UPDATE with
shuttle managers saying launch remains on schedule.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The launch team was making up lost
hours Monday as a hush-hush countdown proceeded toward a
Thanksgiving Eve liftoff of space shuttle Discovery with five
astronauts and a secret spy satellite.
   Workers were several hours behind schedule when the countdown
started Sunday, but NASA reported Monday they were catching up,
doing the lagging work in parallel with other launch preparations.
   Following a three-hour launch readiness meeting Monday, shuttle
managers reported that while the schedule was tight, ``no major
issues are being worked'' and the launch remained on schedule.
   ``We're right on track for a Wednesday night launch; everything
is going fine,'' space agency spokeswoman Lisa Malone reported.
   She said shuttle officials expect all tasks to be on schedule by
late Tuesday.
   Workers had fallen behind in checking out systems and
reinstalling equipment and panels on the bottom sections of the two
solid fuel booster rockets. The panels were removed earlier in the
week so technicians could inspect computer boxes suspected of
having faulty wiring. One of the boxes was replaced.
   Because the mission is classified, NASA remained silent on the
exact status of the countdown. It has said only that liftoff is
scheduled between 7:30 p.m. and 10:30 p.m. and that it will make
the count public just nine minutes before the planned liftoff.
   There also will be a news blackout throughout the mission.
   It will be only the third after-dark launch in 32 shuttle
missions. The last one, in November 1985, was visible for several
hundred miles along the east coast, from Key West at the tip of the
Florida Keys to north Georgia.
   This is the fifth shuttle flight dedicated solely to the Defense
Department. Officials said the secrecy makes it more difficult for
Soviet reconnaissance satellites and a spy ship sitting off Cape
Canaveral to track the shuttle.
   The astronauts assigned to the mission flew to Cape Canaveral on
Sunday from their training base in Houston. They slept during
daylight hours Monday to adjust their schedule to the hours they
will keep in space because of the nighttime launch.
   The commander is Air Force Col. Frederick C. Gregory, the first
black named to command a shuttle mission. The pilot is Air Force
Col. John Blaha, and the mission specialists are Navy Capt. Manley
L. Carter Jr., F. Story Musgrave and Kathryn C. Thornton.
   They are expected to stay in space for four days. Their main
task will be to deploy a satellite which sources close to the
project report will listen in on diplomatic and military
communications in the Soviet Union and other countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891120-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 1843EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Soldier 1stLd-Writethru a0566 11-20 0783</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Soldier, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0566,0804</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldier Commits Suicide After Mock Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with another suicide attempt, quotes
from brother, former chief psychologist, other details. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A soldier in an elite infantry unit killed
himself after comrades beat him and put him through a mock trial in
his underwear, Israeli media reported Monday.
   An army psychologist blamed the death on failure to find a
political solution to the 23-month-old Palestinian uprising in the
occupied territories, which he said was increasing stress among
Israeli soldiers.
   In another suicide report, army sources said a female member of
a unit of settler soldiers tried to take her own life by shooting
herself in the stomach with a pistol in a Tel Aviv store.
   Hospital officials said the 19-year-old woman, whose name was
not released, was in fair condition. No further details were given.
   The suicide of 20-year-old Eli Shahar on Saturday was the second
in the Givati brigade recently. A Givati soldier assigned to the
occupied Gaza Strip shot himself to death two weeks ago.
   Suicides appear to be increasing in the army generally.
   On Monday, the military command said Monday 15 to 39 soldiers
have committed suicide in each of the last seven years, and 24
soldiers took their own lives from April through November 1989. It
did not give figures on suicide attempts.
   A report in the daily Yediot Ahronot said the army was
investigating a total of 45 reported suicides in 1989 and Israel
television put the number at more than 50.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, responding Monday to a question
in Parliament, denied suicide was on the rise in the military. He
said the army tries to prevent it by choosing draftees carefully
and training commanders to recognize signs of distress, Israel
radio reported.
   Dan Bar-On, a professor at Ben-Gurion University in Beersheba
who is a military psychologist in the reserves, said the army was
not equipped to deal with the stress of soldiers serving in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza.
   ``The army can deal with combat shock ... but I think it is not
prepared to see how the present state of stress is different from
the previous ones experienced by the Israeli soldiers,'' he said on
Israel television.
   ``Today, we have a situation of no exit ... and political
leaders who are supposed to offer an exit want to prolong this
situation, to put it mildly. Young people feel that nobody worries
about providing alternatives to the intefadeh,'' as the Palestinian
uprising is known.
   Col. Reuven Gal, formerly chief army psychologist, said
``exposure to events in the territories ... of course increases
pressure and maybe increases the tendency for violence and violent
reactions, but it does not necessarily lead to suicide.''
   An army spokesman confirmed the military was investigating the
case of Shahar, who newspapers said was having trouble with his
commanding officer.
   The daily Hamishmar said masked, older recruits awakened Shahar
on Saturday and carried him into a nearby tent, where they beat him
and threw soup in his face.
   Reports in Yediot and Maariv, two other newspapers, said a mock
trial followed at which Shahar was found guilty of disobedience and
sentenced to four hours of guard duty and a month of kitchen work.
   All three papers reported that Shahar said nothing during the
trial and trembled from fear or cold, dressed only in his underwear
and a helmet.
   Maariv said the unit commander watched the trial and did nothing
to stop it.
   Afterward, Shahar returned to his tent, stuck the barrel of his
assault rifle in his mouth and pulled the trigger, according to
newspaper and radio reports.
   Shahar's brother Avi, a junior officer in another army unit,
demanded the soldiers involved be punished.
   ``It was murder,'' Maariv quoted him as saying. ``He pulled the
trigger, but they brought him to that situation.''
   ``Masked soldiers were waiting. They made Eli turn his back to
them, put a helmet on his head, accused him of some offenses and
sentenced him to four hours of guard duty,'' Avi Shahar said on the
television. ``The platoon commander was there. He was watching.''
   Israel radio reported that in July, a Givati soldier committed
suicide and another shot himself in the foot to escape brutality
from comrades.
   In May, a military court convicted four Givati soldiers of abuse
and sentenced them to nine months in jail for beating a Gaza
Palestinian with a broomstick and rifle butts. The Arab later died
of beatings administered by other soldiers.
   Givati troopers often suppress Palestinian riots in the Gaza
Strip. They have become known for rough and sometimes brutal action.
</TEXT>
