<DOCNO> AP891120-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 2053EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Sciascia     11-20 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Sciascia,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sicilian Novelist Dead at 68</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALERMO, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leonardo Sciascia, a Sicilian novelist
who wrote of the Mafia, official corruption and Italy's political
class, died Monday at age 68, his family reported.
   Asked once whether he feared a Mafia reprisal, Sciascia replied:
``The Mafia doesn't read literature.''
   A family announcement said he died at his home in Palermo,
capital of Sicily, but did not give the cause of death. Sciascia
had suffered for some time from kidney problems.
   He was part of the Sicilian literary tradition of Luigi
Pirandello and Giuseppe di Lampedusa, who explored the character of
people whose lives were molded by the island's history.
   Among Sciascia's best-known works were ``The Day of the Owl,''
``The Sicilian Relatives'' and ``The Wine-Dark Sea,'' a collection
of short stories about Sicilians coping with authority figures.
   He used ``Candido'' _ Voltaire's ``Candide'' moved to Sicily _
to attack the Mafia and politicians.
   ``I have this image of Sciascia ... of a man who had his own
convictions, which he did not intend to abandon,'' said Giulio
Einaudi, Sciascia's publisher from 1958 to 1983. ``His great
strength was the way he could make news events poetical.''
   One of Sciascia's most controversial works, ``The Moro Affair,''
explored the 1978 kidnapping and murder of former Premier Aldo Moro
by the leftist Red Brigades.
   In the book, Sciascia saw the Christian Democratic politician as
left to his fate by a government of his own party that refused to
deal with his captors, ignoring pleas for help written from Moro's
``people's prison.''
   ``I was very interested in the `friends' of Aldo Moro who, from
`this moment on' (so they said), decided he was no longer
himself,'' the novelist told a newspaper interviewer.
   Sciascia lived in Palermo, but considered home to be a farmhouse
in central Sicily, near his birthplace of Racalmuto, where he did
not have a telephone or keep a car.
   The author had a brief fling with party politics in the 1970s,
winning a seat on the Palermo city council as an independent on the
Communist Party ticket.
   His goal was to help in an anti-Mafia cleanup of city politics.
He resigned because of Communist Party overtures to the Christian
Democrats.
   Funeral arrangements were incomplete, and there was no list
immediately available of survivors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
