<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 2054EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Beaches     11-20 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Beaches,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Durban Council Votes to Open Beaches to All Races</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURBAN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council, reversing a vote
taken two weeks ago, decided Monday to open all beaches to all
races in Durban, South Africa's foremost resort city.
   In another desegregation move, the provincial administrator of
Cape Town issued an order opening all beaches under his authority.
Beaches in Cape Town, also a major holiday city, were opened long
ago. But some municipalities in Cape Town province did not take
similar action or decided to defy the declaration by President F.W.
de Klerk last week that all the country's beaches should be
desegregated.
   Municipalities control most beaches, and only they have the
power to legally desegregate them despite de Klerk's announcement.
   The Durban City Council voted Nov. 6 on a proposal to open all
of Durban's beaches, with 16 members approving the measure and 14
opposing it. The proposal failed because a two-thirds majority was
required.
   Later the council agreed to remove signs declaring sections of
the beaches ``whites only',' but the segregation laws remained in
effect.
   On Monday the vote was 24-5 to open all the beaches that were
still reserved for whites. In coming weeks, thousands of
vacationers will arrive in the Indian Ocean city for the holiday
season.
   De Klerk also has called for repeal of the Separate Amenities
Act that allows the segregation of parks, libraries, swimming pools
and other public facilities.
   Parliament is expected to consider repeal when it reconvenes in
February.
   South Africa has a system of apartheid that by law and custom
establishes a racially segregated society in which the 28 million
blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites
control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and
health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
