<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 2058EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Panama-US     11-20 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-US,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Troops Conduct Military Exercise; Panama Objects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIA VICTORIA GONZALEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. troops circled an American
military hospital with armored personnel carriers and barbed wire
Monday in an exercise Panama said violated the canal treaties.
   More than 200 Panamanians shouted anti-American slogans outside
Gorgas Hospital while military officials of the two countries
argued about the maneuver.
   Panamanian women pulled out sections of the coiled wire so some
vehicles could reach government installations in the area. Armored
personnel carriers partially blocked the entrance to Health
Ministry offices, across the street from the hospital.
   Maj. Manuel Rodriguez, a member of a joint U.S.-Panamanian
military board, told U.S. officials the maneuver violated the 1977
treaties, under which the canal is to be turned over to Panama at
the end of 1999, because it obstructed traffic and had not been
cleared with Panamanian officials.
   Sources at the U.S. Southern Command, American military
headquarters, said Panama had been told of the exercise in advance.
   Rodriguez claimed the purpose of the maneuver was ``to hide the
wounded who are coming from El Salvador,'' where hundreds of people
have been killed or wounded in 10 days of some of the heaviest
fighting in the country's decade-old civil war.
   The U.S. army holds regular military exercises, which it says
are necessary to train soldiers defending the Panama Canal.
   Relations between Panama and the United States have deteriorated
in the past two years because of U.S. efforts to have Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega removed as Panama's military commander, a position
from which he controls the government.
   Noriega has been indicted in Florida on federal charges of drug
trafficking and money laundering. He denies the accusations.
</TEXT>
