<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-20 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Winds, Snow Over Michigan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm packing winds up to 78 mph and snow howled over Upper
Michigan on Monday, as temperatures hit 71 degrees in other
sections of the Midwest.
   Snow showers also fell on northwest Minnesota and Maine.
Scattered rain fell along the northern Pacific Coast, the central
Texas coast and northeast New York.
   Much of Upper Michigan's Lake Superior shoreline was under a
winter storm warning that predicted up to a foot of new snow and
wind chills down to 20 degrees below. An advisory warning of snow
and blowing, drifting snow was in effect for northern Lower
Michigan, where up to 7 inches of snow was expected.
   Lakes Erie and Ontario were under storm warnings prompted by the
strong, gusty winds.
   The strongest gusts recorded in Upper Michigan were in Copper
Harbor, where they hit 78 mph. Winds gusting to 60 mph were clocked
in Pellston, Iron Mountain, Ironwood, Whitefish Point and Grand
Marais, and near 50 mph in Saulte Ste. Marie.
   High wind warnings were also issued for western New York state,
Minnesota, Wisconsin and northeast Iowa. Winds gusted over 40 mph
in northern Minnesota and to 51 mph in Dubuque, Iowa, late in the
morning.
   Temperatures were 10 to 20 degrees warmer than normal for the
third week this month. By noon, the mercury had climbed to 71
degrees as far north as Marion, Ill., and Garden City, Kan.
   The weather was also warm in Southern California and
unseasonably cool in New England. Temperatures across the rest of
the nation were generally near normal.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EST ranged from 22
degrees in Caribou, Maine, to 85 degrees in Burbank and Santa
Monica, Calif. The low temperature for the Lower 48 states was 4
degrees in Gunnison, Colo.
</TEXT>
