<FIRST>u a AM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru   11-20 0898</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0691,840</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Campaigns for Pro-Choice GOP Congresswomen</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf 2: ``Flying back,'' with veto of D.C. bill; INSERTS
graf 23: ``In Rhode,''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush campaigned Monday for two
Republican congresswomen whose election would help the GOP in the
Senate but whose views clash with his own veto-enforced opposition
to abortion.
   Flying back to Washington, the president vetoed, for the second
time this year, the annual bill appropriating funds for the
District of Columbia because it would allow the use of local funds
for abortions.
   Bush praised the two women for supporting him on a variety of
matters, saying of Lynn Martin, who is running for the Senate in
Illinois: ``Lynn's been right on issue after issue. ... She thinks
like I do, like you do.''
   He did not mention abortion in his remarks at a Chicago
fund-raising luncheon for Martin, emphasizing instead his reliance
on her on such issues as capital gains taxes and efforts to clean
up the environment.
   Bush later flew to Rhode Island to attend separate fund-raising
events for Senate contender Rep. Claudine Schneider and Gov. Edward
DiPrete, who is seeking a fourth two-year term as Rhode Island's
chief executive.
   Bush called Schneider, who has not declared her candidacy, ``an
independent, principled congresswoman with a proud record of
leadership on the environment, on education and in combating crime.
She's a great representative and I think she'd make a great
senator.''
   Again, Bush steered clear of the abortion issue.
   In remarks at the governor's mansion for DiPrete, Bush said he
was undaunted by this year's congressional defeat on winning a
lower capital gains tax rate.
   ``When Congress starts its new session next year, we're going to
make it absolutely clear that the fight for a capital gains cut is
far from over,'' Bush said.
   Bush also previewed his summit meeting with Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev for the DiPrete supporters, saying ``this is
going to be a historic meeting'' but adding, ``I don't want to
overpromise.''
   He said the meeting presented a good opportunity to enhance
peace prospects. But, he added, ``I will be prudent and be cautious
and keep my eyes open.''
   On other issues during his trip:
   _Presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Bush would
go to Brussels immediately after the Dec. 2-3 summit with Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev to brief NATO leaders.
   _Bush said he hoped for ``meaningful dialogue'' in his
Mediterranean shipboard summit with Gorbachev. ``This meeting will
occur because America has been resolute in defense of liberty,''
Bush said. ``And it will occur amid the changes sweeping East and
Central Europe and bringing freedom to millions who share a common
heritage with so many in Illinois.''
   _Fitzwater said the president would make a 10-minute prime-time
address to the nation Wednesday night, talking about the upcoming
summit and about developments in Eastern Europe.
   As Bush spoke at the $250-a-person GOP fund-raiser in Chicago,
he was heckled by several members of the audience who shouted
criticism of U.S. policy in El Salvador.
   When a woman accused the administration of killing priests, Bush
said: ``We are not. You be quiet.''
   Bush then sought to explain why the U.S. was supporting the
government in El Salvador.
   Then, a second member of the audience, a man, jumped up and
shouted, ``Stop the repression in El Salvador.''
   Four demonstrators, three of them identified as Roman Catholic
nuns by a colleague, were led out and arrested by security forces
as the crowd applauded.
   ``Now, who's next,'' Bush joked. ``I'm here to talk about Lynn.
This is not a town meeting.
   ``We must not pull our support away from a freely elected
government in Central America,'' Bush said.
   In Rhode Island, Bush's motorcade whizzed by two groups of
demonstrators appearing on behalf of the homeless and AIDS patients.
   Before leaving on the trip, Bush cautioned Congress not to cut
off aid for El Salvador, saying it would be unacceptable to him as
president. About mid-day, the House voted on procedural grounds
against including Salvador-aid restrictions in a foreign aid bill.
   Two gubernatorial candidates Bush campaigned for earlier this
fall _ Marshall Coleman in Virginia and Rep. James Courter in New
Jersey _ lost Nov. 7. Both shared Bush's anti-abortion position,
and polls suggested their stands may have contributed to their
defeats.
   Martin, who along with Schneider visited Bush in the White House
last week to air their differences on the abortion issue, was
referred to by Bush as a ``close and dear friend.''
   Both women are seeking to oust incumbent Democratic senators
next year.
   Martin has announced she will try to unseat Sen. Paul Simon in
Illinois, while Schneider is considered the likely challenger to
Sen. Claiborne Pell of Rhode Island.
   While in Chicago, Bush visited Picard Elementary School on
Chicago's south side.
   After Bush's address to schoolchildren in September outlining a
national anti-drug strategy, Picard's teachers had their pupils
write the president about how drugs affected their lives. A letter
from fifth-grader Ana Zamora caught Bush's eye.
   ``I never go outside because my mom gets scared that I'll get
hurt because of the gang fights,'' she wrote.
   On Monday, she got the first question and asked Bush ``how much
do you arrest'' drug users.
   ``We're beginning to make the case that a person who uses drugs
has to pay the penalty,'' he responded.
</TEXT>
