<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Party     11-20 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Party,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Politburo Member Calls for Overhaul of Communist Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Politburo member Marian Orzechowski called
Monday for a complete overhaul of the Communist Party, saying new
members were needed at all levels of the organization, the official
news agency PAP said.
   Orzechowski, who also leads the Communist Party caucus in
Parliament, made the appeal at a meeting of local party officials
in the Baltic port of Gdansk, the agency said.
   The party suffered a historic defeat when it became the first
East bloc party to lose control of the government with the election
of Tadeusz Mazowiecki, a former Solidarity trade union editor, as
prime minister on Aug. 24.
   Since then, the Polish United Workers' Party _ the Communist
Party in Poland but known by its Polish initials as the PUWP _ has
been struggling to find a new direction and has called a Congress
for Jan. 27 to map out a new political strategy.
   But party members are divided over whether to follow the
Hungarian model and form a new party or try to reform the current
organization.
   ``Poland, working people and socialism vitally need strong
socialist political formation. ... It should be a new party
compared to the PUWP, in all aspects of its activities,''
Orzechowski said.
   He told the meeting that ``from the point of view of cadres
there is a necessity for a general generation replacement of party
cadres on all levels. This is he elementary condition of regaining
credibility and getting social trust for the new party.''
   The party is already considering a name change and has decided
that the more than 1,500 delegates to the Congress should be
elected directly.
   Delegates to the Congress are to consider alternative proposals
for reform of the party that have already been presented to the
Central Committee.
   One proposal calls for the creation of a new party of leftist
forces, and the other calls for transformation of the current party
while retaining the present name.
   An internal party survey in September indicated that 72 percent
of the members favored a complete retooling of the party, starting
with its name.
</TEXT>
