<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     11-20 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Claim Soviet Troops Attack Afghan Villages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan rebels said Monday that Soviet
tanks crossed into Afghanistan's northwestern Faryab province and
shelled villages and guerrilla positions near the border.
   A statement issued by a coalition of seven rebel groups
headquartered in Pakistan did not mention any casualties or say
when the purported attack occurred.
   It said a Soviet tank unit shelled areas around Andkhoi, 16
miles from the Soviet border.
   The rebels frequently claim Soviet warplanes raid northern
Afghanistan.
   Meanwhile, Afghanistan's official Radio Kabul reported
government soldiers reopened the strategic Salang highway linking
the capital of Kabul to the Soviet Union.
   The broadcast, monitored in Islamabad, said more than 1,000
supply vehicles reached Kabul.
   Western diplomats have said that for the past several weeks
supply convoys were backed up along the Salang highway north of
Kabul because of rebel attacks and blockades.
   Radio Kabul declared, ``This highway is open forever.''
   The Soviet Union sent troops into Afghanistan in December 1979
to help the Marxist government battle the anti-communist
guerrillas. There were more than 100,000 Soviet military personnel
in Afgnaistan for years, but the Kremlin withdrew the last of its
combat forces in February under a U.N.-brokered agreement.
   Western diplomats have said more than 300 Soviet military
advisers remained in Kabul.
</TEXT>
