<DOCNO> AP891120-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 0854EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-Beijing'sMood Adv29   11-20 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Beijing's Mood, Adv 29,0692</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wednesday PMs, Nov. 29 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Memories of Spring Still Fresh as Beijing Settles in for Winter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only a handful of police remain where soldiers
and tanks filled Tiananmen Square in June, and in place of sandbags
on the streets are piles of cabbages.
   Hundreds of thousands of tons of cabbages have been dumped on
sidewalks throughout Beijing as people stock up for winter _ with
memories still fresh of a bloody spring.
   Some try to get rid of the memories.
   ``I don't think about it,'' a receptionist said. ``I just come,
do my job and go home. Nobody bothers me and I don't pay attention
to anyone.''
   In the spring, the young woman had stayed at her workplace, not
daring to go home for four days after the violent crackdown, which
left hundreds if not thousands dead. Thousands more were arrested
in nationwide sweeps that continue.
   Her neighbor, who was in his early 20s, was killed by a
soldier's bullet the night of June 3 after he went into the streets
to see what was happening.
   The youth's father was ordered to write an essay on how he had
failed to educate his son properly; there was no funeral.
   ``Are you kidding?`` the woman said sarcastically. ``He was a
`counterrevolutionary,' a `thug'.''
   A sullen mood prevails at Beijing's universities.
   In early November, investigators questioned students on the
campus of Beijing University, which was at the forefront of the
protests. All students were warned at rallies to cooperate with the
investigators or they could end up being questioned instead by the
police.
   ``People are still very nervous,'' said a student at the
university who took part in the protests of May and June. ``We
don't know what they will do to us next.''
   A student at Beijing Normal University, another of the activist
schools, declined to meet a foreign acquaintance.
   ``Things are still quite tense,'' she said. ``They're still
investigating people, you know.''
   She said she feared her chances of getting a passport to study
overseas would be in jeopardy.
   On Tiananmen Square, a few dozen People's Armed Police have
replaced army soldiers standing guard. People can enter the square
only with written permission from a work unit.
   The souvenir photo stands have returned, and families come to
have their pictures taken in front of the Gate of Heavenly Peace.
   For 30 fen (8 cents), they can see the Military History Museum's
special exhibit on putting down the demonstrations. Outside the
museum are several burned out tanks and army trucks that became
victims of the crowds when the army thundered in to seize Tiananmen.
   Inside are hundreds of photos of the students who occupied the
square for three weeks. Nearby are smashed loudspeakers,
confiscated Molotov cocktails and newspapers from overseas wrongly
declaring that senior leader Deng Xiaoping had died and that
Premier Li Peng had been shot.
   One section devoted to soldiers who were killed displays their
bloodied clothing, firearms and diaries. There is nothing about
civilian casualties.
   Attendance has also slackened off, from 40,000 visitors a day in
August to about 2,000 now.
   Meanwhile, government television has dropped its drumbeat of
attacks on the ``counterrevolutionary turmoil,'' but
government-produced films showing soldiers being beaten and burned
are still shown.
   One newspaper reported recently that soldier Tian Yuejun had
named his newborn son Pingbao _ ``Putting down the turmoil'' _ so
the child ``will always remember how his father took part in
serving the country and putting down the counterrevolutionary
turmoil.''
   Martial law, imposed on most of Beijing on May 20, remains in
effect, although military sentries were replaced by regular police
Nov. 1.
   ``Nobody feels good will toward the People's Liberation Army or
the People's Armed Police,'' a taxi driver sneered. ``But we're
more scared of the armed police. They've been trained in kung fu
and karate and will be much quicker to beat us up.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs Nov. 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891120-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 0856EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-Cyprus-Watchpost Adv30   11-20 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cyprus-Watchpost, Adv 30,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday PMs, Nov. 30 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cyprus Becomes Key Mideast Listening Post for Major Powers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN MARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States, the Soviet Union and
China are building large new embassies in Nicosia, adding new
emphasis to Cyprus as a key Middle East listening post.
   The divided island in the eastern Mediterranean has more foreign
diplomats, intelligence agents, foreign soldiers and journalists
than larger Arab capitals.
   Its importance as an intelligence-gathering base grew as
Westerners fled war and terrorism in Beirut.
   ``Cyprus really is on the crossroads,'' said Vladimir A.
Chizkhov, first secretary at the Soviet Embassy.
   ``It's a small country but definitely its role is greater than
its size, because it's on the threshhold of the Middle East, and,
of course, it is also the location of the Cyprus problem.''
   Cyprus has been divided since the Turkish army invaded in July
1974, to keep the island, which has a Greek majority, from uniting
with Greece.
   The Turks seized the northern third of the island, which the
Turkish Cypriot minority declared a breakaway republic in 1983.
Only Turkey recognizes it.
   While Greek Cypriot newspapers have described the new Soviet
embassy as a ``palace,'' the U.S. Embassy under construction right
across the street is called a ``fortress.''
   The $30million American building is designed mainly to be secure
against attack. Some walls are nearly three feet thick. Set well
back from the street, the building is surrounded by a high concrete
wall and a double fence.
   Direct access is impossible. Visitors must enter through a gate
away from the main building, then make a sharp turn left and pass
through another gate.
   Metochiou Street, on which U.S. and Soviet embassies are
situated, has gained the nickname ``Microwave Alley'' because of
the potential for the two superpowers to spy on each other.
   The graceful, colonnaded entrance to the new Soviet chancery is
in sharp contrast to the American building; only minimal security
is in evidence.
   The new Chinese embassy is done in pagoda-like architecture.
   Nicosia also has an Israeli Embassy and a mission of the
Palestine Liberation Organization. Israeli Mossad secret service
operatives move about the island along with senior PLO figures, and
Libyan and Syrian agents.
   Iran opened an embassy recently. Canada set up an immigration
office to deal with the flood of Lebanese and Iranians seeking
visas.
   International news organizations, including The Associated
Press, have set up Middle East listening posts in Nicosia as well.
One of their tasks is to monitor Iran's television and radio
broadcasts.
   Cyprus has excellent telecommunications and airline links with
the region.
   Complicated shortwave antannae, large satellite dishes and other
electronic gear litter the roofs of many buildings in Nicosia,
while on the 6,000-foot summit of Mount Olympus, is ``the
golfball,'' a large white geodesic dome that conceals British
electronic surveillance antennae.
   Nearby Ayios Nicolaos is the base for Britain's 9th Signals
Regiment, which conducts electronic intelligence-gathering from the
forested mountains.
   U.S. U-2 reconnaissance planes fly out of the British Royal Air
Force base at Akrotiri on the south coast.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thursday PMs, Nov. 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
