<DOCNO> AP891120-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 1418EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Vatican-Soviet Adv26-1stAdd   11-20 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Vatican-Soviet, Adv 26-1st Add,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Nov. 26, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>VATICAN CITY: of Communists.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In 1963, Soviet leader Nikita S. Khrushchev offered an olive
branch, releasing the leader of the Ukrainian Catholics,
Metropolitan Josef Slipyj, after 18 years in labor camps. Later
that year, John XXIII received Khrushchev's daughter, Rada, and her
husband, Alexis Adzhubei, the editor of the government newspaper
Izvestia.
   The thaw did not mean Khrushchev was softening up on religion at
home. Quite the contrary: in 1959-64, he closed about half the
churches in the Soviet Union. Religion, he predicted, would
disappear by 1980.
   Nonetheless, John XXIII saw an advantage in an opening to the
Soviet bloc. He felt the Communist governments had secured power
and little could be gained by fighting them. He also realized the
regimes themselves were seeking better relations.
   The Vatican's new policy toward the East bloc came into its own
under John's successor, Pope Paul VI. In the 1970s, the Vatican
established diplomatic relations with Yugoslavia and working
contacts with Poland.
   The pope met five times with the long-time Soviet foreign
minister, Andrei A. Gromyko, and received Nikolai Podgorny, the
Soviet president, who then had little power but bore symbolic
importance.
   Concessions from the Soviet bloc did not come easy, however. In
1971, to advance negotiations with Hungary, Paul VI asked Cardinal
Jozef Mindszenty, an outspoken anti-Communist, to leave the U.S.
legation in Budapest where he had taken refuge in 1956. Three years
later, the pope removed him as primate of Hungary.
   Paul VI was accused by critics of abandoning the ``silent
churches'' _ of which Mindszenty was a symbol _ but the strategy
bore results. In Hungary, the Vatican was allowed to name bishops
to fill vacant sees and expand religious instruction.
   The election in 1978 of Cardinal Karol Wojtyla of Poland as Pope
John Paul II, another strong anti-Communist, initially marked a
slowdown in the Vatican-Soviet rapprochement.
   The Soviets criticized the pope in the early 1980s on grounds
that he encouraged the Solidarity labor movement in Poland and
condemned class struggle. For Pravda, John Paul was a ``Reaganite
and the most reactionary pope of the age.''
   On top of that came the attempt to assassinate John Paul in May
1981. Mehmet Ali Agca, the Turkish gunman, claimed he had Bulgarian
and Soviet assistance for his deed. While his allegations were
never proven, the attack further strained Vatican relations with
Moscow.
   But the rise of Mikhail S. Gorbachev in 1985 marked another
dramatic turn in Vatican-Soviet affairs.
   Scores of religious prisoners were freed as Gorbachev
established ``glasnost,'' or greater freedom in public expression.
Arrests of activists plunged.
   In October 1988, the Soviet government told Lithuanians it would
return their cathedral in Vilnius, which had been turned into an
art gallery. More than 20,000 jubilant worshippers flocked to the
first Mass there in 30 years.
   The Vatican has taken advantage of what it calls the Soviets'
``new spirit.'' This year, the Holy See has succeeded in naming
bishops in Lithuania, Byelorussia and Czechoslovakia, forging
diplomatic ties with Poland and arranging a visit by John Paul to
Hungary.
   Big differences remain between the two sides, particularly over
the outlawed Ukrainian Catholic Church. But there have been hints
Moscow is prepared to soften its stance on the Ukrainians.
   ``Concrete signs of this new (Soviet) attitude exist regarding
religion: new churches are opening; they are fixing up those that
already exist,'' Cardinal Jozef Glemp of Poland said after a trip
to the Soviet Union last year.
   ``They are facts _ still sporadic, but real.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891120-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 1418EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Vatican-Soviet-Issues Adv26   11-20 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Vatican-Soviet-Issues, Adv 26,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Nov. 26, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pope-Gorbachev Meeting Could Assure Papal Visit to Soviet Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Friday in 2nd graf is Dec. 1.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Vatican-Soviet, b0695-b0696</HEAD>
<HEAD>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An invitation for the first papal trip to
the Soviet Union could be the crowning prize of Pope John Paul II's
meeting with Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The pope's long-expressed wish to visit his flock in the Ukraine
and other Soviet regions is one of the main issues expected to be
discussed during his official audience with the Soviet president
Friday.
   John Paul will want to press his case for religious freedom,
legalization of the Ukrainian Catholic Church and normalization of
the status of the church in the Baltic republics, whose annexation
by Moscow has never been recognized by the Vatican.
   But analysts say Gorbachev also will be looking for something
from the pope, such as a pledge to use his influence to stem the
nationalist movements that are threatening Gorbachev's reforms.
   Gorbachev and the first Polish-born pope do have some things in
common, including a vision of a united Europe, though with a
different emphasis. Gorbachev espouses a ``common European home,''
while John Paul sees Christianity as Europe's unifying force.
   Church and Soviet officials and John Paul himself have expressed
increased optimism that the meeting with Gorbachev will clear the
way for a pastoral visit to the Soviet Union, home to an estimated
8 million to 10 million Roman Catholics.
   The pope has ruled out a ``political visit'' limited to Moscow.
He has said he wants to travel throughout the country to visit
Roman Catholics in areas such as the Ukraine, Lithuania, Latvia,
Byelorussia and Kazakhstan.
   A major roadblock remains the status of the Ukrainian church,
which was brutally suppressed in 1946 by the Stalin dictatorship
and forcibly merged with the Russian Orthodox Church.
   Ukrainian Catholics, who practice the Byzantine rite, have
emerged from the underground in the past two years to openly demand
official recognition by Moscow. By Western estimates, at least 4
million Ukrainians are Catholics.
   ``Our position is very simple,'' said the Vatican-based Cardinal
Myroslav Lubachivsky of the Ukraine. ``We want our church to be
legalized. We want to retain our Byzantine rite and we want to be
under the jurisdiction of the pope.''
   Church officials say Soviet authorities have adopted a more
tolerant attitude toward Ukrainian Catholics but point out that top
Russian Orthodox officials remain opposed to legalization. Among
other things, the Orthodox church would stand to lose hundreds of
churches it took over when the Ukrainian Catholics were persecuted.
   The pope also wants greater freedom for the church in
Byelorussia, for which he was recently able to appoint the first
bishop in more than 60 years, and for the Baltic republics of
Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia, areas where nationalist and
independence movements are strong. In Lithuania, an estimated 80
percent of the 3 million people are Roman Catholics.
   The Vatican is also concerned about the shortage of churches and
priests for the Catholics of German and Polish origin who live in
Kazakhstan, Tadzhikistan, Kirgizia and Soviet Georgia.
   One way the Vatican hopes to remedy the situation is by setting
up a permanent office of contact between the Holy See and the
Kremlin. This could be arranged during Gorbachev's visit and
possibly lead to the establishment of full diplomatic relations,
church officials say.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
