<DOCNO> AP891120-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 1500EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Colombia'sWar Adv26   11-20 1108</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Colombia's War, Adv 26,1142</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Nov. 26, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Colombians See Political System as Obstacle to War on Drugs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fear is growing among Colombians that
they may lose the war against drug traffickers, not through a lack
of determination, but because of a political system they see as
immature and in its worst crisis ever.
   ``Drug traffickers are not the cause of Colombia's problems;
they are the worst manifestations of a severe political malaise,''
said Clara Lopez, a former candidate for mayor of Bogota, the
nation's capital.
   Other Colombians agree with her view that the government cannot
defeat drug traffickers and their private armies through military
confrontation alone.
   Lopez said the government may be forced to rally more of the
population to its cause through political reform, staunchly
resisted in the past.
   If the government refuses reform, she added, it could face the
prospect of a society fatally wounded, not by the drug traffickers,
but by its own internal divisions.
   Lopez was one of the leaders of a splinter faction of the
Liberal Party in the early 1980s. It was headed by Luis Carlos
Galan, who later returned to the mainstream Liberal fold.
   A leading candidate for the presidential election set for next
May, Galan was assassinated by drug traffickers Aug. 18 _ a deed
that prompted President Virgilio Barco to declare all-out war on
the drug cartels.
   Lopez and other politicians of similar view maintain that while
Colombia's two main parties, the Liberals and the Conservatives,
are going after traffickers, they have failed to attack the roots
of the country's problems.
   Among these problems, they say, is a failure to encourage the
participation in the political process of many sectors of society.
   ``According to the tourist guides, Colombia is a democracy, but
the reality is quite different,'' Lopez said in an interview.
   She was referring to a small class of elites that has held power
for generations over a mass of politically and economically
dispossessed.
   In Bogota, officials in luxury automobiles, surrounded by
machinegun-toting outriders, make the daily trip into Bogota from
the wealthy northern neighborhoods, weaving around urban buses
packed with tired, perspiring people from the southern part of the
city.
   The scene in Bogota's traffic symbolizes what many see as the
alienation of the people from their government, not just in Bogota,
but in cities and rural sections across the country.
   ``In many cases people simply don't consider the possiblity that
that they have a right to determine the future of their
communities,'' said Kathy Gladden, a U.S. anthropologist who has
studied the organization of garment workers in Colombia.
   Lopez said the government, for example, has not given community
councils a say in how tax money should be spent.
   ``We have the power to change the names of public parks and
plazas, but that's about it,'' she said.
   The domination of the system by the two mainstream parties has
frustrated many Colombians and forced them to turn to political
violence, she said.
   The fate of the 4-year-old leftist Patriotic Union Party is
indicative of the perils of trying to work within the system.
Right-wing death squads have killed 737 of the party's members.
   Also threatening the country's stability, along with the drug
traffickers, are six leftist guerrilla groups.
   Javier Torres, a professor of political science at the Los Andes
University in Bogota, also contends a democratic opening is
necessary to prevent further fragmentation of Colombian society.
   He said each of the 13 presidential candidates, whose views
range from left to right, probably would carry on some sort of
reform program as president. But he added, the reforms may not be
enough or be the ones needed the most.
   Barco is to turn the presidency over to the winner on Aug. 7; he
is forbidden by the constitution from running for another four-year
term.
   Torres said that Colombian politicians, wary of destabilizing
the accepted order, have traditionally taken a cautious approach to
reforms and that the trend is likely to continue.
   He said the more conservative candidates like Hernando Duran
Dussan, a former Bogota mayor, would concentrate on improving the
country's industrial sector while moving very slowly to encourage
greater political participation.
   Duran Dussan, the epitome of the Liberal Party's old guard and
regarded as a hardliner, is one of the three front-runners in the
campaign.
   The other two, Cesar Gaviria and Ernesto Samper, are also
members of the Liberal Party, but they represent a younger
generation that is perhaps more open to reform.
   The Conservative Party, weakened by internal division, is given
little chance of winning in May.
   Torres said that while the Barco administration instituted some
important changes, such as the popular election of mayors, it has
not responded to demands for the election of governors or for other
reforms.
   Critics say the reforms needed most to keep the country from
exploding are a more efficient justice system, government financing
of presidential campaigns, the election of governors, a strict
accounting of government spending, land reform and more local
government autonomy.
   In the current judicial setup, judges lack the autonomy to
direct criminal investigations and prosecutions and must seek the
cooperation of political appointees.
   ``Investigations are often determined by political interests,
and it is in the government's interest to keep things that way,''
Torres said.
   Lopez, the former mayoral candidate, pointed to the scores of
judges slain in recent years as an indication societal tension has
risen to an intolerable point. Drastic reform is needed to prevent
an even bigger bloodbath, she said.
   ``Right now standing still in this country is the same as moving
backward,'' she said. ``If our next government is reactionary,
civil war will break out in Colombia.''
   It would not be the first time. The killing in 1948 of Jorge
Eliecer Gaitan, who was seen as a progressive leader, frustrated
Colombians' hopes for change and started a war called ``The
Violence.'' More than 250,000 people were killed from 1948 to 1953.
   According to Lopez, the government best equipped to avoid a
repetition of ``The Violence'' would be headed by someone who is
willing to change the system and is supported by a coalition of
reformists from both parties.
   At National University in Bogota, Professor Pilar Gaitan said
the election of a hardliner would ``result in a repressive
administration.'' But she added that a large segment of Colombian
society views an authoritarian approach as the only way to solve
the country's problems.
   ``Many people, faced with such a deep crisis, have moved to the
far right,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
