<DOCNO> AP891120-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 2337EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   11-20 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   Chamber music, by Francis Poulenc (London) _ Pascal Roge, piano;
Patrick Gallois, flute; Maurice Bourgue, oboe; Michel Portal,
clarinet; Amaury Wallez, bassoon; Andre Cazalet, horn.
   
   London straddles two worlds in its recent chamber music
releases, from the Slavicized Germanic tradition of Dohnanyi to
Poulenc's Gallic charm and incision. This compact disc exhibits the
bulk of the latter's chamber works for winds: the big-boned sextet;
sometimes similar sounding sonatas for clarinet, flute and oboe;
and the captivating trio for oboe, bassoon and piano.
   We hear an idiomatic interpretation of quintessential French
music, recorded in Paris. These players bring the expected high
level of wind-playing of Poulenc's country folk. Always smooth, and
never less than tasteful, they sometimes reach the level of
blandness in the sextet.
   Roge should be commended for his light, airy playuing and
attention to detail. Bourgue stands out among the winds,
particularly for his singing lines.
   _ By Daniel Wakin, Associated Press Writer
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Cindy Bullens'' (MCA) _ Cindy Bullens
   
   The guitar-based pop-rock of Cindy Bullens will sound familiar
to anyone who has heard the guitar-based pop-rock of Bryan Adams.
   But while ``Cindy Bullens'' loses points for lack of
originality, the album gets high marks as a collection of tough but
catchy songs with plenty of energy and fine singing. There's enough
variety to sustain interest, too, from the ballad ``Letters of
Fire'' to the thundering ``Cry for Love'' and the r&amp;b-styled
``Where Did I Hide My Heart?''
   Co-producer Bob Clearmountain, whose credits include Adams and
Tina Turner, comes up with a mix that's clean but still has plenty
of crunch, much of it contributed by guitarist David Mansfield.
Adams himself helps out by singing harmony on one cut.
   Bullens' closest brush with fame has been as a backup vocalist
for Elton John. She sings much of the time like Chrissie Hynde or
Pat Benatar, and it's clear she's still looking for a distinctive
sound. It's just as clear she has the talent to find it.
   _ By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
