<FIRST>r f PM-ChannelOne     11-20 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Channel One,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whittle Claims 1,050 Schools Have Signed Up for Channel One</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,000 schools have signed three-year
contracts to receive the commercially-sponsored Channel One daily
news show for the classroom that debuts in March, Whittle
Communications said.
   The 1,050 signups have already exceeded Whittle's startup target
of having 1,000 schools participating in the service by the launch
date.
   Channel One will provide daily 12-minute news programs geared
toward teens that are to be shown in classrooms during the school
day.
   The news shows also will include two minutes of paid advertising
for products such as candy bars and deodorant. The commercials have
triggered outcries from some national education groups and state
education officials in California and New York state who say it is
wrong to permit companies to pitch products to a captive audience
of students.
   Several cable networks have tailored commercial-free programs to
the school audience, notably Turner Broadcasting Systems Inc.'s
Cable News Network, which is airing a daily 15-minute news show
overnight to be taped for use in the classroom.
   But schools participating in Channel One receive free equipment
as well as programming. Each is given dozens of television
monitors, a satellite dish and videocassette recorders that Whittle
says would cost them $40,000 to $50,000 if they bought them on
their own.
   The shows are transmitted overnight to the schools for replay on
the monitors during the school day.
   Whittle Chairman Christopher Whittle said in a statement Sunday
the schools signed up to date are in 29 states, including seven of
the 10 largest, and have 739,000 students.
   He said his sales people have approached officials in 1,740
school districts, and that 440 have signed up while 221 have
rejected the service outright. Talks are continuing with the other
districts, and Whittle hopes to offer the service to schools in all
50 states.
   He said he is confident that the project will meet its goal of
having 7,000 to 8,000 schools with an enrollment of 6 million
students participating by the end of 1990.
   Whittle previously said that he has signed up advertisers who
have committed about $50 million for the first year of the service
and nearly $150 million for the first three years.
   His first-year ad revenue target is $90 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
