<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 1019EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EC-EastGermany     11-20 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EC-East Germany,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germany Seeks Political, Economic Ties with EC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany has told the European
Community it wants a broad trade and economic cooperation accord
with the EC and also hopes to start political consultations on
European security matters.
   But it made clear there can be no discussion of a German
reunification.
   In a letter, sent last Friday, to the 12 EC governments, East
German Prime Minister Hans Modrow, asked that ``negotiations for a
trade agreement, also taking into account the requirement for
economic cooperation, should start as soon as possible.''
   The letter, a copy of which was obtained by The Associated
Press, states East German wishes for a relationship going far
beyond that which the EC has forged with other emerging East
European democracies, notably Hungary and Poland.
   ``The German Democratic Republic would like to develop its
relations with the European Community speedily, cooperatively and
constructively,'' the letter states.
   Modrow said he wants cooperation in economic relations, trade,
science, technology, the environment, transport, fisheries, the
standardization of industrial norms, statistics ``as well as in the
humanitarian field, culture, education and information.''
   He also wrote:
   ``We are ready for a political dialogue about questions of
security and peace in Europe'' but made clear there can be no
discussion of changing the border between East and West Germany.
   EC officials had no immediate comment Monday on the letter.
   It was sent to the 12 EC capitals one day before the EC leaders
met in Paris on Saturday to assess the frantic changes now sweeping
Eastern Europe.
   At their summit, the leaders pledged to step up aid to Eastern
Europe if democracy firmly takes root there and agreed to study the
creation of a development bank for Eastern Europe.
   Polnd and Hungary _ two nations that are to benefit from $1.1
billion in long-term EC loans and $333 dollars in short-term aid _
already have signed trade and economic cooperation agreements with
the Community.
   Talks for a simple trade accord between the EC and East Germany
are in a preliminary stage. EC External Relations Commissioner
Frans Andriessen will go to East Berlin ``soon'' to speed up the
talks following the Nov. 9 opening of East German borders, an EC
official said Monday.
</TEXT>
