<FIRST>u f PM-PSNHBankruptcy     11-20 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-PSNH Bankruptcy,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northeast Utilities Chosen to Take Over Public Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOINA CHIACU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After almost two years of wrangling and
uncertainty, New Hampshire's largest electric utility appears ready
to emerge from bankruptcy under new ownership that seems to have
state and industry support.
   Northeast Utilities of Hartford, Conn., came out of last-minute
negotiations between shareholders and creditors Saturday as the
winning bidder to take over Public Service Co. of New Hampshire and
its 36 percent share of the Seabrook nuclear plant that forced it
into bankruptcy.
   The tentative agreement on Northeast's $2.3 billion takeover
proposal was to be presented today to U.S. Bankruptcy Judge James
Yacos. It calls for annual rate increases of 5.5 percent for seven
years.
   Shareholders and creditors of Public Service still must take a
formal vote on the Northeast plan and any others still on the
table. Then Yacos will hold confirmation hearings to make sure the
chosen plan will do what it says it will do.
   Public Service's investors stand to lose about $1.6 billion in
the utility's reorganization, with shareholders absorbing the brunt
of the loss, an attorney said.
   ``It's a pretty significant loss ... that is primarily being
suffered by shareholders,'' said Howard Berman, an attorney for the
shareholders.
   New Hampshire Gov. Judd Gregg, who announced the tentative
agreement, withheld official endorsement of the Northeast plan
until state negotiators can go over it once more.
   ``There still are many uncertainties to be resolved before this
case is concluded,'' Public Service spokesman Nicholas Ashooh said.
   Other New England utilities have raised the possibility of
antitrust action.
   Northeast is New England's largest electric utility, and Public
Service has almost 400,000 customers in New Hampshire.
   State legislators still must meet in a special session, expected
to be scheduled today, before Jan. 1 to vote on whether to modify a
state law that bans advance charges for Seabrook before it begins
commercial operation. Every takeover proposal relied on an
electricity rate plan that called for rate increases beginning Jan.
1, and those rates would include Seabrook costs.
   Several attempts in the past to repeal the law have failed.
   Senate Majority Leader Edward Dupont and House Speaker Douglas
Scamman said they thought chances are good that the law will be
modified.
</TEXT>
