<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lack of Export Business Sends Soybeans Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean prices closed lower Monday on
the Chicago Board of Trade as selling to take profits weighed on
soybean futures.
   Soybean futures were on the defensive throughout the day because
of commercial fund selling, analyst Joel Karlin of Research
Department Inc. said.
   Karlin said the selling was technical in nature on the
perception that soybean futures were overbought. Futures also were
pressured by a lack of export business.
   Corn prices were lower due to a spillover effect from the
selloff in the soybean pits, although corn futures received support
from reports of Far East buying and news that Mexico may enter the
market this week.
   Wheat prices received a boost from concerns about dry weather
conditions in the winter wheat crop region, Karlin said. The latest
six- to 10-day forecast by the National Weather Service is calling
for continued dry conditions in the Central Plains.
   At the close, wheat was a { cent to 2\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.10{ a bushel; corn was a \
cent to 2} cents lower with December at $2.37\ a bushel; oats were
1} cents to 2\ cents lower with December at $1.45{ a bushel;
soybeans were 8\ cents to 10{ cents lower with November at $5.75\
cents a bushel.
</TEXT>
