<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 1535EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-DenverPostContracts     11-20 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Denver Post Contracts,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Denver Post Unions Approve Contracts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five unions representing Denver Post employees
have ratified contracts with the newspaper, including one local
that organized a 14-month circulation boycott campaign after taking
steep pay cuts.
   Unions representing mailers, typographical workers, paper
handlers, stereotypers and pressmen ratified contracts with the
newspaper Sunday.
   The Post had been locked in a dispute with Denver Mailers Union
Local 8, whose members load delivery trucks and operate machines
that insert supplements, since the paper cut mailroom employees'
wages by 42 percent to 52 percent in August 1988.
   ``We are gratified that The Denver Post and its employees have
entered into a renewed partnership for the future,'' Post Chairman
W. Dean Singleton said. ``With this cooperation between labor and
management, The Post is poised for excellent growth in the years
ahead.''
   The mailers' agreement establishes a three-year timetable for 55
journeymen mailers to draw within 11 percent of the wages they
received before the cuts were made in 1988.
   Another 22 less-experienced mailers will get smaller wage
increases than the journeymen. The mailers union also represents
about 100 part-time employees.
   ``We were not overwhelmingly pleased, but we were forced to
accept reality,'' mailers local president Ray Benoit said.
   During the boycott campaign, the union urged Post subscribers in
radio advertisements to cancel their subscriptions. Despite the
effort, the newspaper recently released circulation figures showing
an increase in subscribers.
   The agreements between the company and the other four unions
call for 160 union members to receive $500 bonuses in each of the
next two years and a 4 percent wage increase in the final, third
year of the contract.
   The paper handlers accepted a company offer to extend the
contract to five years. They are to receive a 4 percent wage
increase in the fourth year and a 5 percent increase in the fifth
year.
   Machinists and engravers unions considered but did not vote on
the company proposal and said they would seek to reopen talks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
