<DOCNO> AP891120-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 1539EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Greece-Television     11-20 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Television,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Private Commercial Television Station Opens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A commercial television station owned by
five newspaper publishers went on the air Monday, ending a state
monopoly and promising objectivity in news and variety in
entertainment programs.
   At least two more private channels are preparing to go on the
air soon, following a law passed in October allowing independent
television broadcasts.
   Nikos Skoulas, managing director of the new ``Mega Channel,''
said at the start of the first transmission that the independent
station was dedicated to improving the quality of television.
   The channel will present Greek, European and American movies,
television serials, sports and variety and game shows. It will
operate for 10 hours on weekdays and 11 hours on weekends.
   Employees of the state-run Hellenic Radio Television Corporation
(ERT) staged several work-stoppages in September protesting the
government proposal to allow independent television stations.
   Until Monday, ERT controlled the nation's only two television
stations.
   The state monopoly on radio and television broadcasts began to
crumble in 1987 when the Athens municipality set up a radio
station, prompting the socialist government at the time to legalize
independent radio stations.
   There are 42 municipal and commercial radio stations in the
greater Athens area, in addition to scores of others around the
country.
</TEXT>
