<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 1528EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Brazil-Economy Bjt   11-20 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Economy, Bjt,0785</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Potentially Explosive Economic Problems Await Brazil's Next President
^By STAN LEHMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nation on the brink of
hyperinflation, burdened with huge foreign and internal debts, is
the potentially explosive economic scenario awaiting Brazil's next
president.
   But only painful recessionary economic policies can deactivate
the hyperinflation time bomb and the next chief-of-state may not
have the time or the support to implement such policies, say
economists and businessmen.
   ``If the next president does not act quickly to undertake real
economic adjustments then his political authority and credibility
will be greatly weakened,'' says U.S. economist Jeffrey Sachs.
   ``The real essence of Brazil's economic future will probably be
decided in the first few weeks of the new government,'' he said.
   The challenge will fall to either conservative Fernando Collor
de Mello or Marxist Luis Inacio Lula da Silva, who compete Dec. 17
in a presidential runoff election.
   Collor de Mello, of the center-right National Reconstruction
Party, led a field of 21 candidates in the Nov. 15 election,
Brazil's first free balloting for president in 29 years. The former
state governor had 28.4 percent of the votes, with 99.3 percent of
the ballots counted Monday.
   Da Silva, a former trade union president of the radical left
Workers Party, was second with 16.1 percent.
   Both candidates say restarting economic growth is the top
priority.
   The new president who takes office next Mar. 15 will confront an
annual inflation rate of more than 1,300 percent; a foreign debt of
about $110 billion, the largest in the Third World; an internal
government debt of $120 billion; and a public deficit equal to 6
percent of the country's $350 billion gross national product.
   ``The cure for high inflation is the sharp contraction of the
budget deficit which can be achieved by cutting public spending,
reducing subsidies and increasing taxes and public utility rates,''
Sachs said at a recent seminar in Sao Paulo.
   Government intervention in the economy was common under the
military regime that ruled Brazil from 1964 to 1985. That policy
continued under President Jose Sarney, who took power in a 1985
election controlled by the outgoing generals.
   Sachs said his proposed economic stabilization measures would
provoke a recession that would last about one yer, after which he
predicted Brazil's economy would start recovering.
   Economist Joaquim Eloi Cirne de Toledo, of the University of Sao
Paulo, warned that the next president might not have the popular
and political support needed to adopt economic austerity measures.
   ``When the next president takes office, the monthly inflation
rate probably will be about 65 percent, which is not enough to
destabilize the economy,'' Toledo said.
   ``If the economy is not about to collapse, it will be difficult
to convince congress and the public of the urgent need for
austerity measures...'' Toledo said.
   By April, 1990, inflation will be about 70 percent a month,
Toledo said. He predicted the new government then would impose
price and wage controls that would bring inflation down to 6 or 7
percent.
   ``But inflation would soon start accelerating again and by the
end of the year it will be 80 percent a month,'' he said.
   ``At this stage hyperinflation will probably explode and only
then will the new president have the public support to restructure
the economy.''
   Toledo said the restructuring would a require a reduction of the
public deficit by renegotiating longer repayment periods and lower
interest rates on Brazil's internal debt.
   The internal debt is financed by government securities that pay
more than 1 percent daily interest rates.
   Brazil also must negotiate longer repayment terms and lower
interest rates on its foreign debt, on which it currently pays
$14.5 billion annually, said Toledo.
   John Mein, executive vice-president of the American Chamber of
Commerce, said in an interview that Brazil's next president may not
have enough time to adopt the measures needed to eliminate the
threat of hyperinflation.
   ``The presidential honeymoon with the people and Congress could
last between 45 days and six months; hardly enough time to set in
motion the structural changes in the economy needed to bring
inflation under control,'' Mein said.
   Mein said the new government must open up the economy to more
foreign investment, diminish its interference in the economy,
privatize badly managed and unprofitable state enterprises and
institute tax reforms to close loopholes that encourage widespread
tax evasion.
   The government also will have to devalue the new cruzado,
Brazil's currency, by at least 30 percent to make local goods more
competitive on the international market, Mein said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891120-0213 </DOCNO>
