<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 1808EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Competitiveness     11-20 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Competitiveness,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gephardt, Heinz Hit Administration on World Competition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Richard A. Gephardt, the Democratic
leader of the House, and Sen. John Heinz, a prominent Republican,
joined Monday in criticizing the Bush administration for cutting
back support for making the United States competitive in high
technology.
   Heinz, R-Pa., a member of the Senate Banking Committee,
emphasized concerns that cut across party lines.
   ``As a Republican, I feel very strongly that it would be a
mistake for my party and the Bush administration to discover that
our failure to comprehend reality had irreparably undermined ths
nation's national security and its ability to remain a world
leader,'' he told a news conference.
   Gephardt denounced what he called the ``high priests'' of free
trade and free markets.
   ``There are people who believe ... that other economies around
the world operate exactly like ours and that the free-market
ideology and the free-trade ideology reign in practice everywhere
in the world,'' he said.
   ``The problem with that belief is that, I think, it is out of
synchronization with reality,'' Gephardt said. ``So what America
has to do is to fashion a public-private cooperation so that we can
compete in the world as it is.''
   Both legislators noted a report issued Monday on U.S.
telecommunications policy by a private group, the Economic Policy
Institute. It predicted a loss of 2 million U.S. jobs by the year
2010 and an annual trade deficit $225 billion larger than it would
otherwise be unless the government helps U.S. industry compete
against Japan and Western Europe.
   The most critical areas, according to the report, are
television, computers, digital communications and semiconductors,
the electronic chips now at the heart of all telecommunications.
   The study concluded that, unlike its economic rivals, the United
States has failed to set up a system for staying competitive in
leading communications technologies.
   In a statement to the Senate on Sunday, Heinz cited another
report made public Monday, this one from the National Advisory
Committee on Semiconductors. That committee included government
officials as well as leaders in the industry.
   ``The U.S. merchant semiconductor industry has lost its dominant
world market share in the past 10 years,'' the panel's report said.
``Because technological leadership is cumulative, once
technological leadership is lost it is very difficult to regain.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
