<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 1911EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-FoodPrices     11-20 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Food Prices,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thanksgiving Meal More Expensive This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The traditional Thanksgiving meal of
turkey, cranberries, stuffing and pie will cost more this year, a
Purdue University economist says.
   Food prices rose about 5 percent in 1989, compared with a 4
percent increase from 1987 to 1988, said agricultural economist
Joseph N. Uhl.
   ``And these price increases are likely to continue through 1989
and into 1990,'' Uhl said.
   The good news for Thanksgiving is that turkey prices are lower
this year because of increased supplies and more grocery specials.
Ham costs about the same as it did last year, Uhl said.
   Because of bad weather last winter and spring, the cranberry
crop is about 4 percent smaller than last year. Wheat prices also
are up, meaning breads and stuffing will be more expensive. The
size of the sweet potato crop has declined by 1 percent from 1988.
   Almonds, hazelnuts, pistachios and pecans will be in shorter
supply for holiday baking and snacking this year, although peanuts
and walnuts will be plentiful, the economist said.
   Vegetable prices, especially for potatoes, onions, tomatoes and
lettuce, will remain relatively high for the rest of the year, he
said.
   Prices for holiday baking supplies also are higher this year.
   ``The effects of the 1988 drought and this year's strong U.S.
and worldwide demand for food products has caused sugar, flour,
shortening, eggs and butter to rise,'' Uhl said.
   Even oatmeal cookies will be more expensive, due to the
increased demand for oats, and chocolate prices will be somewhat
higher as supplies decrease. However, pumpkins are plentiful for
holiday pies.
   Holiday beverages will cost more this year. Coffee prices are
down, but orange juice and soda are up. Milk and dairy prices are
substantially higher, and higher prices for eggs means more
expensive eggnog.
   Uhl blamed the drought, tighter food supplies and a strong
consumer demand for food for raising the price of eggs, milk, bread
and beef.
   ``Further price increases can be expected in coming months,'' he
said. ``Normally, for perishable products, it takes three months
for the full effects of a farm price increase to be reflected in
grocery store prices.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891120-0217 </DOCNO>
