<FIRST>u f BC-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru f0129 11-20 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0129,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Again Trying to Sell Latin Routes to American Airlines</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: ADDS new grafs 1-3 to UPDATE with confirmation from American;
picks up 3rd graf pvs bg'ng, The Journal, ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines is trying again to work out a deal
to sell its Latin American routes and other assets to rival
American Airlines, a spokesman said Monday.
   ``They approached us again. We've had some occasional
discussions concerning their Latin American network,'' said Jim
Brown, a spokesman for American at its headquarters in Dallas-Fort
Worth, Texas. ``We are receptive to assets purchases. No
announcement is imminent.''
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell declined comment on details of
the negotiations published by The Wall Street Journal.
   The Journal, quoting unidentified sources, said negotiations
began about 10 days ago and continued through this past weekend.
The sources said the talks included close telephone contact between
Frank Lorenzo, the chairman of Eastern's parent Texas Air Corp.,
and Chairman Robert Crandall of AMR Corp., parent of American.
   The Journal report said the Latin American routes, valued at
$365 million, are part of a $400 million to $500 million assets
package.
   Speculation that Eastern would renew efforts to sell the
lucrative routes was fueled earlier this month because some
creditors were concerned about cash shortfalls in Eastern's
rebuilding plan.
   Hit by a crippling strike March 4, Eastern filed five days later
for Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization.
   Miami-based Eastern has been rebuilding as a smaller carrier
without the unions, after selling off a number of assets to pay its
debts.
   However, extended talks with American, keenly interested in the
Latin American routes as it builds up its Miami operations,
foundered about three months ago. At that time, Eastern said it
would keep the routes and planned to emerge from Chapter 11 early
next year at as much as 90 percent of its pre-strike size.
   But that meant Eastern had to overhaul its reorganization plan
for creditors. The carrier recently received a 60-day extension of
its filing deadline for the revised plan.
   The Journal said a major sticking point to be overcome in
negotiations was a lawsuit that Continental Airlines, Eastern's
sister carrier, has pending against American in a dispute over
computer reservations. Continental has been seeking as much as $1
billion in damages.
   That suit undercut the earlier talks between Eastern and
American, the nation's largest airline, according to the newspaper.
   A source said American wanted whatever amount it paid to settle
that suit to be included in the Latin American package in a way
that would show as little as possible. The package being negotiated
also includes some Continental routes and airport gates, the report
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
