over-the-counter market, totaled 154.35 million shares.
   Aerospace issues tumbled after Richard Cheney, secretary of
Defense, called over the weekend for a $180 billion reduction in
military spending over the next six years.
   United Technologies dropped 3} to 50|; Litton Industries 8[ to
76]; Lockheed 3| to 35~; Raytheon 6} to 68|; Martin Marietta 4{ to
39{; General Dynamics 4~ to 44[, and Grumman 1 to 17.
   An exception was Boeing, up 1{ at 59{ following the weekend news
of a tentative settlement between the company and machinists who
have been on strike for six weeks.
   The possibility of long-term reductions in defense spending has
been widely discussed on Wall Street with the recent opening up of
many East-West political barriers in Europe
   Otherwise, analysts said traders found little reason to chase
after stocks.
   The government is due to report Tuesday on the consumer price
index for October. Analysts expect the data to show about a 0.4
percent increase, up from 0.2 percent in September.
   The figures aren't expected to go ver far in resolving the
debate on Wall Street over whether the recent slowing of the
economy will lead to a recession and continued downward pressure on
corporate earnings in 1990.
   Losers among the blue-chip industrials included International
Business Machines, down ] at 98}; General Electric, down ] at 59[;
