<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Fall Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices in London fell sharply Monday on
worries about the pound and a weak start on Wall Street.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down 38.3
points, or 1.7 percent, at 2,183.1, also its session minimum. It
began the session off just 1.1 points at 2,220.3.
   Volume amounted to a modest 364.9 million shares, compared with
507.5 million shares Friday.
   Some dealers said the drop across the board came as players
began anticipating Thursday's release of British trade figures,
which analysts expect to show a further deterioration.
   But other dealers said they didn't see any wholesale dumping of
positions. Many said it was a typically sluggish Monday with little
substantive news to move share prices.
   After the market's recent sharp technical rally, some market
watchers contended that the move higher over the last month might
finally be coming to an end, as players begin to focus more
squarely on the condition of the British economy.
