<FIRST>u f AM-McCaw-Lin 1stLd-Writethru f0184 11-20 0742</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-McCaw-Lin, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0184,0761</SECOND>
<HEAD>McCaw Sweetens Offer For LIN, Asks LIN to Put it to Shareholder Vote</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6-7th grafs pvs, Lin offered ... to update with LIN statement,
closing stock prices. Picks up 8th graf pvs, Analysts said ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The long-running battle for LIN Broadcasting
Corp. took another twist Monday as McCaw Cellular Communications
Inc. increased its cash tender offer for a controlling interest in
LIN by $625 million to $3.4 billion.
   McCaw also said that if its offer succeeded, it would have LIN
borrow $425 million to buy McCaw stock which then would be
distributed to remaining LIN shareholders.
   ``Our amended offer, which has a value more than $800 million
higher than our earlier offer, is clearly the superior alternative
for LIN's shareholders,'' said McCaw's chairman and chief
executive, Craig O. McCaw.
   McCaw challenged the New York-based cellular telephone and
broadcasting company to put its new offer to a vote at the
previously scheduled January meeting, at which LIN's shareholders
are being asked to accept a rival offer from BellSouth Corp., the
regional telephone company based in Atlanta.
   The Kirkland, Wash.-based McCaw said that if LIN refuses, it
intends to ``take our case directly to the LIN stockholders'' by
mounting a proxy fight for control of the LIN board.
   LIN said its board would review the revised proposal ``on a
timely basis,'' but urged its shareholders against tendering to
McCaw until its board announced its recommendation. BellSouth said
it was studying the revised offer but that its first reading
indicated its own deal with LIN offered more ``strength and value''
to LIN shareholders.
   In trading in the over-the-counter market, LIN climbed $4.37{ a
share to $120.12{ while McCaw fell $1.25 to $35.75. BellSouth rose
50 cents a share to $51.75 on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Analysts said they valued McCaw's new offer at $123 to $128 a
share, compared with $110 to $113 a share under McCaw's previous
offer and $117 to $124 a share under the BellSouth offer.
   BellSouth is expected to sweeten its offer.
   McCaw, the nation's largest cellular company, has been pursuing
LIN since early June. But LIN has resisted and agreed instead to
merge its cellular operations with those of BellSouth in a deal
that would create a cellular company larger than McCaw.
   Under its latest offer, McCaw said it pay $150 a share for 22.5
million LIN shares, or $3.4 billion. Its previous offer was $125
per share for 22 million shares, a total of $2.75 billion.
   McCaw already owns about 5.1 million LIN shares, and the revised
offer would give it 51.2 percent of LIN's 53.9 million shares,
fully diluted.
   In addition, McCaw said that as soon as possible after the
tender offer is completed McCaw would have LIN buy $425 million of
McCaw stock and distribute it to LIN shareholders, at a value of
$16.17 in stock for each LIN share held.
   The new offer expires at midnight EST Dec. 15, although it would
be extended until the LIN shareholder meeting if LIN puts the bid
to a vote.
   Under the deal with BellSouth, LIN shareholders would get a cash
dividend of $42 a share, stock in the new cellular company that
would be created by the merger of LIN and BellSouth cellular
interests and stock in a new company that would consist of LIN's
seven television stations.
   The participants in both deals have offered guarantees that LIN
shareholders who hold on to their stock in the cellular company
will get private market value for it several years down the road.
   The BellSouth-LIN deal is being submitted to a vote of LIN
shareholders on Jan. 12 and McCaw wants its proposal considered
then also.
   BellSouth and LIN said in announcing their merger deal in
October that they felt the deal could be closed in the first
quarter of 1990.
   But McCaw said regulatory approvals could delay the
BellSouth-LIN deal for up to a year. McCaw said its deal could be
closed much sooner and said it would demonstrate its confidence in
that by pledging to pay interest of 12 percent annually on its cash
tender offer if the offer closes after March 31, 1990.
   McCaw said last week it has received firm commitments totaling
$3 billion from a 22-bank syndicate, which, with about $1.2 billion
of its own cash and marketable securities, is enough to complete
the tender offer.
</TEXT>
