<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-20 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0736</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fears Over Economy Send Copper Prices Lower</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices were sharply lower Monday on New York's
Commodity Exchange as worries about the U.S. economy fueled a
selloff that began last week.
   On other markets, precious metals and energy futures were
higher, while grain, soybean, livestock and pork futures were lower.
   Copper settled .60 cent to 3 cents lower with the contract for
delivery in November at $1.062 cents a pound.
   News that copper stocks in London Metal Exchange-approved
warehouses increased by 12,000 metric tons weighed on the market.
Analysts said the increase in stocks indicates the economy is
weakening.
   ``Copper is an industrial metal, and an economic slowdown means
less building of homes (where copper is used in pipes) and less
industrial uses,'' said analyst Peter Cardillo of Josephthal &amp; Co.
in New York.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney's remarks Sunday that there could
be major cuts in defense spending was also seen as a bad sign for
copper.
   Precious metal futures rallied on the Comex as prices on the New
York Stock Exchange fell and the U.S. Treasury bond market
retreated.
   Cardillo said gold prices also were influenced by the failure of
producers to sell at current prices. He said that gloom over
government figures indicating a slowing economy also were a boost
to prices.
   Gold was $3.50 to $3.70 higher with November at $398.20 a troy
ounce; silver was 1.6 cents to 2.9 cents higher with November at
$5.688 a troy ounce.
   Grain and soybean prices closed lower on the Chicago Board of
Trade as selling to take profits weighed on soybean futures.
   Analyst Joel Karlin of Research Department Inc. said the selling
was technical in nature on the perception that soybean futures were
overbought. Futures also were pressured by a lack of export
business.
   Corn prices were lower due to a spillover effect from the
selloff in the soybean pits, although corn futures received support
from reports of Far East buying and news that Mexico may enter the
market this week.
   Wheat prices received a boost from concerns about dry weather
conditions in the winter wheat crop region, Karlin said. The latest
six- to 10-day forecast by the National Weather Service is calling
for continued dry conditions in the Central Plains.
   Wheat was } cent to 2{ cents higher with December at $4.10} a
bushel; corn was { cent to 2} cents lower with December at $2.37\ a
bushel; oats were 1} cents to 2\ cents lower with December at
$1.45{ a bushel; soybeans were 8{ cents to 10} cents lower with
November at $5.75\ cents a bushel.
   Energy futures were higher on the New York Mercantile Exchange,
with the rally led by heating oil.
   A cold snap on the East Coast last week generated interest in
heating oil on expectation of increased consumer demand, said
analyst Jerry Samuels of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Also acting as a spur to prices is the coming meeting in Vienna
of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries ministers.
   ``You don't sell before OPEC meetings,'' Samuels said.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 3 cents to 16 cents higher
with December at $20.07 a barrel; heating oil was .53 cent to .81
cent higher with December at 60.08 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .27 cent to .50 cent higher with December at 52.22
cents a gallon.
   Livestock and pork futures were lower on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   The drop in hog futures reflected lower cash market prices, said
analyst Mike Swinford of Balfour Maclaine Corp. in Chicago. Frozen
pork bellies were lower due to the rejection Friday by the U.S.
Department of Agriculture of offers for purchases of pork bellies
to ship to Poland.
   Cattle prices were mostly lower, but received some support from
higher cash prices, Swinford said.
   Live cattle were .30 cent lower to .35 cent higher with December
at 75.22 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .30 cent
lower with November at 83.10 cents a pound; hogs were .27 cent to
.50 cent lower with December at 49.47 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .98 cent to 1.30 cents lower with February at 62.90
cents a pound.
</TEXT>
