<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     11-20 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower; Gold Continues To Climb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against most major foreign
currencies Monday as traders were scared off by central bank
intervention and the possibility that U.S. interest rates might
decline.
   Gold prices continued to climb.
   Traders said the dollar fell after the central banks of several
countries, including the Federal Reserve and the Bank of Japan,
sold the U.S. currency in hopes of forcing it lower.
   The dollar also was hurt by signs of progress from Washington on
budget cuts, said Jack Barbanel, a foreign exchange analyst with
First Global Asset Management Inc.
   Congressional leaders said Monday they were close to agreement
on a bill reducing the federal budget deficit, while Defense
Secretary Dick Cheney was considering $180 billion in military
spending cuts over the next six years.
   Budget cuts might give the Federal Reserve Board some leeway to
allow interest rates to fall, Barbanel said. If rates decline in
the United States while remaining high overseas, the dollar would
be less attractive to foreign investors.
   In earlier trading abroad, the dollar was mixed. Dealers said
the dollar initially rose on reports of planned military spending
cuts, but the currency was unable to maintain its advance.
   Late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday's
prices, included: 1.8338 West German marks, down from 1.8410;
1.62975 Swiss francs, down from 1.6307; 6.2435 French francs, down
from 6.2630; 1,350.00 Italian lire, down from 1,355.00; and 1.7105
Canadian dollars, up from 1.6945.
   The British pound fell sharply against the dollar, prompting the
Bank of England to buy pounds for dollars. Dealers said there was
some nervousness about the October British trade figures due on
Thursday in view of increasing deficits in recent months.
   In London, one pound cost $1.5595, cheaper for buyers than late
Friday's $1.5705, and in New York, the pound fell to $1.5582 from
$1.5670 late Friday.
   Other rates for the dollar in Europe late Monday, compared with
Friday's late rates, included: 1.8360 West German marks, down from
1.8410; 1.6315 Swiss francs, unchanged; 6.2465 French francs, down
from 6.2590; 2.0760 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0770; 1,351.00
Italian lire, down from 1,353.50; and 1.1712 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.1697.
   Earlier in Tokyo the dollar closed at 144.67 Japanese yen, up
from 143.98 yen. In London, the dollar closed lower at 144.50 yen,
but it rose in New York to 144.355 yen from late Friday's 144.25.
   Gold bullion prices continued the steady upward climb of the
past three weeks and dealers said they expected to see the $400
level tested soon.
   In New York, Republic National Bank quoted a late bid of $398
for a troy ounce of gold, up $3.75. On the Commodity Exchange of
New York, a troy ounce rose $3.60 to $398.20.
   In earlier London trading, gold closed at a bid $396.50 a troy
ounce, up from $392.25. The closing bid price in Zurich was
$396.65, up from $391.50.
   In Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid $396.40, up from $392.05.
   Silver rose 1.6 cents to $5.688 a troy ounce on the Commodity
Exchange. In earlier London trading, silver was quoted at $5.74 bid
a troy ounce, up from $5.61.
</TEXT>
