<FIRST>r f AM-GreatNorthern     11-20 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Great Northern,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Audubon Society Seeks Protection of Great Northern Woodlands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FALMOUTH, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Maine Audubon Society asked lawmakers
Monday to protect vast land holdings at stake in the
Georgia-Pacific Corp.'s attempted takeover of Great Northern
Nekoosa Corp. from developers.
   The environmental concerns came one day after Atlanta-based
Georgia-Pacific upped its bid to $63 a share from $58 a share.
Great Northern's board planned to meet Tuesday to discuss the offer.
   Great Northern, incorporated in Maine but based in Norwalk,
Conn., has said it has no interest in being purchased. Great
Northern stock closed at $61.62{ in New York Stock Exchange trading
Monday, up 62{ cents.
   Georgia-Pacific has said it does not plan to sell any of the
lands to developers to pay for the takeover, some state officials
and environmentalists are worried that could happen.
   ``Control of the state's timberlands, so vital to the
prosperity, quality of life and Maine's people, rests in Wall
Street, not at home,'' Audubon Society Executive Director Thomas
Urquhart said in a letter to Gov. John R. McKernan and legislative
leaders.
   ``Here at home, the Georgia-Pacific and Great Northern Nekoosa
forest lands are real places with exceptional values to our
citizens for recreation, wildlife habitat and sustainable
employment,'' he wrote. ``They are not merely assets on a ledger.''
   Urquhart said the Audubon Society wants the timber companies to
agree that Great Northern's 2.1 million acres of Maine will remain
in use as forest lands with no change in public use.
   If they refuse, he said the state Legislature should pass a law
requiring companies to prevent forest lands from being developed.
   The Audubon Society said it had no specific proposals for
protecting the land. Urquhart suggested drafting an easement giving
forestry or conservation rights to the land.
   McKernan already has asked the two timber companies for stronger
assurances that certain woodlands would be protected. The Audubon
Society said it supported the governor's efforts but wanted further
guarantees.
</TEXT>
