<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 1828EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MSA-Dun&amp;Bradstreet 1stLd-Writethru   11-20 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-MSA-Dun &amp; Bradstreet, 1st Ld-Writethru,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dun &amp; Bradstreet Agrees to Buy MSA, Software Outfit, for $333 Million</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with stock price, add quotes from MSA
chairman and analyst.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dun &amp; Bradstreet Corp. said Monday it had agreed
to buy mainframe computer software maker Management Science America
Inc. for $333 million in cash.
   New York-based Dun &amp; Bradstreet said the companies reached a
definitive merger agreement at a price of $18.50 a share after
unanimous approval by MSA's board of directors.
   MSA's stock rose $6 a share to $18.12{ a share in
over-the-counter trading, a gain of about 50 percent.
   The two companies are close and leading competitors in providing
mainframe software for general ledger accounting, accounts payable,
accounts receivable and inventory control.
   Although mainframe computers are perceived as dinosaurs by some,
the software segment the companies serve is growing a healthy 16
percent a year. The deal comes at a difficult time for Dun &amp;
Bradstreet, a $4.3 billion business information company which last
week announced an expensive overhaul of its credit-services
operation after widespread consumer complaints. The company said
per-share earnings would fall about 10 percent next year.
   Atlanta-based MSA recently returned to profitability. It earned
about $10 million in the first nine months of this year after
losses of $20 million in the same period a year earlier. It is less
than a tenth the size of Dun &amp; Bradstreet, with $196 million in
revenue through the first three quarters.
   Dun &amp; Bradstreet said it would merge MSA with its own slightly
smaller McCormack &amp; Dodge software operation to create a new
organization with its own board of directors, Dun &amp; Bradstreet
Software Services.
   The company will focus on products for mainframe computers made
by International Business Machines Corp., but will also make
software for Digital Equipment Corp. computers and ``certain other
vendors,'' Dun &amp; Bradstreet said.
   MSA's chairman and chief executive, John P. Imlay Jr., will be
chairman and principal executive officer of the new unit. Frank H.
Dodge, president of McCormack &amp; Dodge, will be vice chairman.
   ``Given the constant changes in the very competitive software
and services industry, this merger is a tremendous opportunity for
both organizations,'' Imlay said in a statement.
   Completion of the deal depends on clearance by antitrust
authorities, which could take time because the businesses overlap
so closely. But Imlay said in an interview that the business is
``so big, with so many competitors,'' that he did not expect a
problem.
   The deal also depends on Dun &amp; Bradstreet being tendered a
majority of the outstanding shares by the current MSA shareholders.
Toward that goal, Dun &amp; Bradstreet said it already had commitments
from holders of 40 percent of MSA's shares.
   One of the MSA shareholders that agreed to tender its shares was
IBM, which bought a 5 percent stake earlier this year. In addition,
Imlay himself owns about 16 percent of the shares and is tendering
them.
   In an effort to reassure customers, Dun &amp; Bradstreet said the
products of both MSA and McCormack &amp; Dodge would be preserved and
enhanced. Sometimes companies try to save money by eliminating
overlapping products.
   Charles Federman, a partner in the investment banking firm of
Broadview Associates of Fort Lee, N.J., said some customers might
desert in spite of the assurances. ``Users have just had their
status un-quoed,'' he said.
   But Imlay, in an interview, denied there was anything to fear.
``Both of us has a history of great customer service and that's why
we're together, really,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
