<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 2054EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-PSNHBankruptcy     11-20 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PSNH Bankruptcy,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>United Illuminating To Drop Bid For PSNH</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE RECHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Connecticut utility said Monday it
would drop out of the bidding for Public Service Company of New
Hampshire if an endorsed offer by another Connecticut power company
holds up.
   United Illuminating of New Haven, Conn., made the decision after
an announcement Saturday that creditors and shareholders had
endorsed a bid by Northeast Utilities of Berlin, Conn.
   Public Service also has made a proposal to bring itself out of a
22-month-old bankruptcy reorganization. Public Service lawyer
Richard Levin said the utility has not decided whether to stay in
the competition. Levin said Public Service first wants to study the
Northeast proposal.
   Larry Smukler, the state's chief negotiator in the bankruptcy
negotiations, said the state would not comment on the plan until it
had studied it, ``although we anticipate agreement.''
   The comments came in the first U.S. Bankruptcy Court session
since Public Service creditors signed on to the $2.3 billion
Northeast buyout proposal.
   Bankruptcy Judge James Yacos gave Northeast until 5 p.m. next
Monday to submit its agreement to parties in the case, the first
bankruptcy of a major utility since the Great Depression.
   If shareholders, creditors and the state still agree on
Northeast Utilities' consensual plan, United Illumniating said it
would withdraw its proposal.
   Northeast also said it hoped to reach agreement with the state
on a rate plan by the end of the week.
   Despite the creditors' backing, shareholders and creditors still
must take a formal vote and the judge will make a final ruling on
the proposals.
   Also Monday, officials set a tentative Dec. 14 date for a
special legislative session to amend or repeal a state law that
bars charging ratepayers for power plants before they operate.
   The three plans for the utility call for rate increases
effective Jan. 1 to begin paying for the Seabrook nuclear plant,
making any change in the law necessary by that date.
   Completed in 1986, the plant remains idle for lack of a federal
operating license, but its owners expect it to begin operating
early next year.
   The Northeast plan calls for annual 5.5 percent rate increases
in each of the next seven years, but allows for additional hikes if
fuel costs skyrocket or Northeast is unable to earn a specified
return on its investment.
</TEXT>
