<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 1901EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     11-20 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices rose in moderate trading
Monday, boosted by colder weather and technical factors.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the December contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil,
rose 16 cents to finish at $20.07 a 42-gallon barrel. Analysts said
late buyers helped push the contract higher before its expiration
at the close of trading.
   The January crude contract also gained 16 cents to close at
$19.99 a barrel.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, No. 2 heating oil
for December delivery rose 0.81 cent to 60.08 cents a gallon. The
January contract gained 0.78 cent to 59.88 cents and February
increased 0.70 cent to 58.73 cents a gallon.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline rose 0.27 cent to 52.22 cents a
gallon, while the January contract climbed 0.38 cent to 52.98 cents
a gallon.
   Analysts attributed Monday's gains partly to technical factors
after last week's technical losses.
   Cold weather in some parts of the nation also helped boost
heating oil prices, they said, while reports of possible supply
disruptions stemming from this weekend's fire at a Chevron refinery
gave gasoline futures a lift.
   A petroleum distillation unit was damaged during the blaze at
the El Segundo, Calif., plant, but no damage estimates were
released.
   Energy analysts said underlying optimism ahead of Saturday's
meeting of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries is
helping support prices, although it is difficult to say how much of
a factor it is in actual buying and selling.
   ``We're starting to see the mentality get a little more
positive, but I wouldn't call it a bullish mentality,'' said Tom
Bentz, director of futures trading for United Energy Inc. in New
York.
   OPEC is scheduled to meet in Vienna, Austria, starting Saturday
to set strategy for 1990, including production allocations for each
of the 13 member countries.
</TEXT>
